# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: codon-reassignment
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] Amino acids can be classified according to the locations of the core structural functional groups (alpha- (α-), beta- (β-), gamma- (γ-) amino acids, etc.); other categories relate to polarity, ionization, and side-chain group type (aliphatic, acyclic, aromatic, polar, etc.).
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] In the form of proteins, amino-acid *residues* form the second-largest component (water being the largest) of human muscles and other tissues.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] Beyond their role as residues in proteins, amino acids participate in a number of processes such as neurotransmitter transport and biosynthesis.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] It is thought that they played a key role in enabling life on Earth and its emergence.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] Amino acids are formally named by the IUPAC-IUBMB Joint Commission on Biochemical Nomenclature in terms of the fictitious "neutral" structure shown in the illustration.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] For example, the systematic name of alanine is 2-aminopropanoic acid, based on the formula CH3−CH(NH2)−COOH.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] The first few amino acids were discovered in the early 1800s.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] In 1806, French chemists Louis-Nicolas Vauquelin and Pierre Jean Robiquet isolated a compound from asparagus that was subsequently named asparagine, the first amino acid to be discovered.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] Cystine was discovered in 1810, although its monomer, cysteine, remained undiscovered until 1884.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] Glycine and leucine were discovered in 1820.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] The last of the 20 common amino acids to be discovered was threonine in 1935 by William Cumming Rose, who also determined the essential amino acids and established the minimum daily requirements of all amino acids for optimal growth.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] The unity of the chemical category was recognized by Wurtz in 1865, but he gave no particular name to it.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] The first use of the term "amino acid" in the English language dates from 1898, while the German term, *Aminosäure*, was used earlier.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] Proteins were found to yield amino acids after enzymatic digestion or acid hydrolysis.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] In 1902, Emil Fischer and Franz Hofmeister independently proposed that proteins are formed from many amino acids, whereby bonds are formed between the amino group of one amino acid with the carboxyl group of another, resulting in a linear structure that Fischer termed "peptide".
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] 2-, alpha-, or α-amino acids have the generic formula H2NCHRCOOH in most cases, where R is an organic substituent known as a "side chain".
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] Of the many hundreds of described amino acids, 22 are proteinogenic ("protein-building").
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] It is these 22 compounds that combine to give a vast array of peptides and proteins assembled by ribosomes.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] Non-proteinogenic amino acids may arise through nonribosomal peptide synthesis.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] Modified amino acids, by contrast, typically result from post-translational modification.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] Amino acids with the structure NH+3−CXY−CXY−CO−2, such as β-alanine, a component of carnosine and a few other peptides, are β-amino acids.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] Ones with the structure NH+3−CXY−CXY−CXY−CO−2 are γ-amino acids, and so on, where X and Y are two substituents (one of which is normally H).
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] The carbon atom next to the carboxyl group is called the α–carbon.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] In proteinogenic amino acids, it bears the amine and the R group or side chain specific to each amino acid, as well as a hydrogen atom.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] With the exception of glycine, for which the side chain is also a hydrogen atom, the α–carbon is stereogenic.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] All chiral proteinogenic amino acids have the L configuration.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] They are "left-handed" enantiomers, which refers to the stereoisomers of the alpha carbon.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] A few D-amino acids ("right-handed") have been found in nature, e.g., in bacterial envelopes, as a neuromodulator (D-serine), and in some antibiotics.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] Rarely, D-amino acid residues are found in proteins, and are converted from the L-amino acid as a post-translational modification.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] Five amino acids possess a charge at neutral pH.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] Often these side chains appear at the surfaces on proteins to enable their solubility in water, and side chains with opposite charges form important electrostatic contacts called salt bridges that maintain structures within a single protein or between interfacing proteins.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] Many proteins bind metal into their structures specifically, and these interactions are commonly mediated by charged side chains such as aspartate, glutamate and histidine.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] Under certain conditions, each ion-forming group can be charged, forming double salts.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] The two negatively charged amino acids at neutral pH are aspartate (Asp, D) and glutamate (Glu, E).
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] The anionic carboxylate groups behave as Brønsted bases in most circumstances.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] Enzymes in very low pH environments, like the aspartic protease pepsin in mammalian stomachs, may have catalytic aspartate or glutamate residues that act as Brønsted acids.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] There are three amino acids with side chains that are cations at neutral pH: arginine (Arg, R), lysine (Lys, K) and histidine (His, H).
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] Arginine has a charged guanidino group and lysine a charged alkyl amino group, and are fully protonated at pH 7.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] Histidine's imidazole group has a pKa of 6.0, and is only around 10% protonated at neutral pH.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] Because histidine is easily found in its basic and conjugate acid forms it often participates in catalytic proton transfers in enzyme reactions.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] The polar, uncharged amino acids serine (Ser, S), threonine (Thr, T), asparagine (Asn, N) and glutamine (Gln, Q) readily form hydrogen bonds with water and other amino acids.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] They do not ionize in normal conditions, a prominent exception being the catalytic serine in serine proteases.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] This is an example of severe perturbation, and is not characteristic of serine residues in general.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] Threonine has two chiral centers, not only the L (2*S*) chiral center at the α-carbon shared by all amino acids apart from achiral glycine, but also (3*R*) at the β-carbon.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] The full stereochemical specification is (2*S*,3*R*)-L-threonine.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] Because of the presence of phenolic hydroxyl group with a pKa = ~10, tyrosine is best classified as a neutral polar amino acid, but with amphipathic character that makes it less polar than classical small polar amino acid residues.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] Nonpolar amino acid interactions are the primary driving force behind the processes that fold proteins into their functional three dimensional structures.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] None of these amino acids' side chains ionize easily, and therefore do not have pKas.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] Several side chains are not described well by the charged, polar and hydrophobic categories.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] Glycine (Gly, G) could be considered a polar amino acid since its small size means that its solubility is largely determined by the amino and carboxylate groups.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] However, the lack of any side chain provides glycine with a unique flexibility among amino acids with large ramifications to protein folding.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] Cysteine (Cys, C) can also form hydrogen bonds readily, which would place it in the polar amino acid category, though it can often be found in protein structures forming covalent bonds, called disulphide bonds, with other cysteines.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] These bonds influence the folding and stability of proteins, and are essential in the formation of antibodies.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] Proline (Pro, P) has an alkyl side chain and could be considered hydrophobic, but because the side chain joins back onto the alpha amino group it becomes particularly inflexible when incorporated into proteins.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] Similar to glycine this influences protein structure in a way unique among amino acids.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] Selenocysteine (Sec, U) is a rare amino acid not directly encoded by DNA, but is incorporated into proteins via the ribosome.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] Selenocysteine has a lower redox potential compared to the similar cysteine, and participates in several unique enzymatic reactions.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] Pyrrolysine (Pyl, O) is another amino acid not encoded in DNA, but synthesized into protein by ribosomes.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] It is found in archaeal species where it participates in the catalytic activity of several methyltransferases.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] The 20 canonical amino acids can be classified according to their properties.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] Important factors are charge, hydrophilicity or hydrophobicity, size, and functional groups.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] These properties influence protein structure and protein–protein interactions.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] The water-soluble proteins tend to have their hydrophobic residues (Leu, Ile, Val, Phe, and Trp) buried in the middle of the protein, whereas hydrophilic side chains are exposed to the aqueous solvent.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] (In biochemistry, a residue refers to a specific monomer *within* the polymeric chain of a polysaccharide, protein or nucleic acid.) The integral membrane proteins tend to have outer rings of exposed hydrophobic amino acids that anchor them in the lipid bilayer.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] Some peripheral membrane proteins have a patch of hydrophobic amino acids on their surface that sticks to the membrane.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] In a similar fashion, proteins that have to bind to positively charged molecules have surfaces rich in negatively charged amino acids such as glutamate and aspartate, while proteins binding to negatively charged molecules have surfaces rich in positively charged amino acids like lysine and arginine.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] For example, lysine and arginine are present in large amounts in the low-complexity regions of nucleic-acid binding proteins.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] There are various hydrophobicity scales of amino acid residues.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] Some amino acids have special properties.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] Cysteine can form covalent disulfide bonds to other cysteine residues.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] Proline forms a cycle to the polypeptide backbone, and glycine is more flexible than other amino acids.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] Glycine and proline are strongly present within low complexity regions of both eukaryotic and prokaryotic proteins, whereas the opposite is the case with cysteine, phenylalanine, tryptophan, methionine, valine, leucine, isoleucine, which are highly reactive, or complex, or hydrophobic.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] For example, a signaling protein can attach and then detach from a cell membrane, because it contains cysteine residues that can have the fatty acid palmitic acid added to them and subsequently removed.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] The common natural forms of amino acids have a zwitterionic structure, with −NH+3 (−NH+2− in the case of proline) and −CO−2 functional groups attached to the same C atom, and are thus α-amino acids, and are the only ones found in proteins during translation in the ribosome.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] In aqueous solution at pH close to neutrality, amino acids are energetically favored in their zwitterionic form, with a deprotonated CO−2 group and a protonated NH+3 group, because the high dielectric constant of water and its hydrogen-bonding network effectively stabilize separated charges.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] Thus, the overall structure is NH+3−CHR−CO−2, and the so-called "neutral forms" −NH2−CHR−CO2H are not present to any measurable degree at physiological pH.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] In strongly acidic conditions (pH below 3), the carboxylate group becomes protonated and the structure becomes an ammonio carboxylic acid, NH+3−CHR−CO2H.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] This is relevant for enzymes like pepsin that are active in acidic environments such as the mammalian stomach and lysosomes, but does not significantly apply to intracellular enzymes.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] In highly basic conditions (pH greater than 10, not normally seen in physiological conditions), the ammonio group is deprotonated to give NH2−CHR−CO−2.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] Although various definitions of acids and bases are used in chemistry, the only one that is useful for chemistry in aqueous solution is that of Brønsted: an acid is a species that can donate a proton to another species, and a base is one that can accept a proton.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] This criterion is used to label the groups in the above illustration.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] The carboxylate side chains of aspartate and glutamate residues are the principal Brønsted bases in proteins.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] Likewise, lysine, tyrosine and cysteine will typically act as a Brønsted acid.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] Histidine under these conditions can act both as a Brønsted acid and a base.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] For amino acids with uncharged side-chains the zwitterion predominates at pH values between the two p*K*a values, but coexists in equilibrium with small amounts of net negative and net positive ions.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] At the midpoint between the two p*K*a values, the trace amount of net negative and trace of net positive ions balance, so that average net charge of all forms present is zero.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] This pH is known as the isoelectric point p*I*, so p*I* = ⁠1/2⁠(p*K*a1 + p*K*a2).
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] For amino acids with charged side chains, the p*K*a of the side chain is involved.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] Thus for aspartate or glutamate with negative side chains, the terminal amino group is essentially entirely in the charged form −NH+3, but this positive charge needs to be balanced by the state with just one C-terminal carboxylate group is negatively charged.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] This occurs halfway between the two carboxylate p*K*a values: p*I* = ⁠1/2⁠(p*K*a1 + p*K*a(R)), where p*K*a(R) is the side chain p*K*a.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] Similar considerations apply to other amino acids with ionizable side-chains, including not only glutamate (similar to aspartate), but also cysteine, histidine, lysine, tyrosine and arginine with positive side chains.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] Amino acids have zero mobility in electrophoresis at their isoelectric point, although this behaviour is more usually exploited for peptides and proteins than single amino acids.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] Zwitterionic amino acids exhibit minimal solubility at their isoelectric point, and in some cases can be isolated from aqueous solution by adjusting the pH to the appropriate isoelectric value.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] Although one-letter symbols are included in the table, IUPAC–IUBMB recommend that "Use of the one-letter symbols should be restricted to the comparison of long sequences".
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] In addition to the specific amino acid codes, placeholders are used in cases where chemical or crystallographic analysis of a peptide or protein cannot conclusively determine the identity of a residue.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] They are also used to summarize conserved protein sequence motifs.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] The use of single letters to indicate sets of similar residues is similar to the use of abbreviation codes for degenerate bases.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] In addition, many nonstandard amino acids have a specific code.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] For example, several peptide drugs, such as Bortezomib and MG132, are artificially synthesized and retain their protecting groups, which have specific codes.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] Bortezomib is Pyz–Phe–boroLeu, and MG132 is Z–Leu–Leu–Leu–al.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] To aid in the analysis of protein structure, photo-reactive amino acid analogs are available.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] These include photoleucine (**pLeu**) and photomethionine (**pMet**).
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] Amino acids are the precursors to proteins.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] They join by condensation reactions to form short polymer chains called peptides or longer chains called either polypeptides or proteins.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] These chains are linear and unbranched, with each amino acid residue within the chain attached to two neighboring amino acids.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] In nature, the process of making proteins encoded by RNA genetic material is called *translation* and involves the step-by-step addition of amino acids to a growing protein chain by a ribozyme that is called a ribosome.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] The order in which the amino acids are added is read through the genetic code from an mRNA template, which is an RNA derived from one of the organism's genes.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] There are 22 amino acids that get naturally incorporated into polypeptides; these are called *proteinogenic amino acids* or *natural amino acids*.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] Of these, 20 are encoded by the universal genetic code.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] The remaining 2, selenocysteine and pyrrolysine, are incorporated into proteins by unique synthetic mechanisms.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] Selenocysteine is incorporated when the mRNA being translated includes a SECIS element, which causes the UGA codon to encode selenocysteine instead of a stop codon.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] Pyrrolysine is used by some methanogenic archaea in enzymes that they use to produce methane.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] It is coded for with the codon UAG, which is normally a stop codon in other organisms.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] The 20 amino acids that are encoded directly by the codons of the universal genetic code are called *standard* or *canonical* amino acids.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] A modified form of methionine (*N*-formylmethionine) is often incorporated in place of methionine as the initial amino acid of proteins in bacteria, mitochondria and plastids (including chloroplasts).
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] Other amino acids are called *nonstandard* or *non-canonical*.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] Most of the nonstandard amino acids are also non-proteinogenic (i.e. they cannot be incorporated into proteins during translation), but two of them are proteinogenic, as they can be incorporated translationally into proteins by exploiting information not encoded in the universal genetic code.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] The two nonstandard proteinogenic amino acids are selenocysteine (present in many non-eukaryotes as well as most eukaryotes, but not coded directly by DNA) and pyrrolysine (found only in some archaea and at least one bacterium).
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] The incorporation of these nonstandard amino acids is rare.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] For example, 25 human proteins include selenocysteine in their primary structure, and the structurally characterized enzymes (selenoenzymes) employ selenocysteine as the catalytic moiety in their active sites.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] Pyrrolysine and selenocysteine are encoded via variant codons.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] For example, selenocysteine is encoded by stop codon and SECIS element.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] Aside from the 22 proteinogenic amino acids, many *non-proteinogenic* amino acids are known.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] These either are not found in proteins (for example carnitine, GABA, ornithine) or are not produced directly and in isolation by standard cellular machinery.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] For example, hydroxyproline is synthesized from proline, and selenomethionine is produced by metabolic modification of methionine.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] Non-proteinogenic amino acids that are found in proteins are formed by post-translational modification.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] Such modifications can also determine the localization of the protein, e.g., the addition of long hydrophobic groups can cause a protein to bind to a phospholipid membrane.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] Some non-proteinogenic amino acids are not found in proteins.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] Examples include 2-aminoisobutyric acid and the neurotransmitter gamma-aminobutyric acid.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] Non-proteinogenic amino acids often occur as intermediates in the metabolic pathways for standard amino acids – for example, ornithine and citrulline occur in the urea cycle, part of amino acid catabolism (see below).
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] A rare exception to the dominance of α-amino acids in biology is the β-amino acid beta alanine (3-aminopropanoic acid), which is used in plants and microorganisms in the synthesis of pantothenic acid (vitamin B5), a component of coenzyme A.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] Many proteinogenic and non-proteinogenic amino acids have biological functions beyond being precursors to proteins and peptides.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] In humans, amino acids also have important roles in diverse biosynthetic pathways.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] Defenses against herbivores in plants sometimes employ amino acids.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] However, not all of the functions of other abundant nonstandard amino acids are known.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] Animals ingest amino acids in the form of protein.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] The protein is broken down into its constituent amino acids in the process of digestion.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] The amino acids are then used to synthesize new proteins and other nitrogenous biomolecules, or they are further catabolized through oxidation to provide a source of energy.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] The oxidation pathway starts with the removal of the amino group by a transaminase; the amino group is then fed into the urea cycle.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] The other product of transamidation is a keto acid that enters the citric acid cycle.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] Glucogenic amino acids can also be converted into glucose, through gluconeogenesis.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] Of the 20 standard amino acids, nine (His, Ile, Leu, Lys, Met, Phe, Thr, Trp and Val) are called essential amino acids because the human body cannot synthesize them from other compounds at the level needed for normal growth, so they must be obtained from food.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] In addition, cysteine, tyrosine, and arginine are considered semiessential amino acids, and taurine a semi-essential aminosulfonic acid in children.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] Some amino acids are conditionally essential for certain ages or medical conditions.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] Essential amino acids may also vary from species to species.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] The metabolic pathways that synthesize these monomers are not fully developed.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] Amino acids are sometimes added to animal feed because some of the components of these feeds, such as soybeans, have low levels of some of the essential amino acids, especially of lysine, methionine, threonine, and tryptophan.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] Likewise amino acids are used to chelate metal cations in order to improve the absorption of minerals from feed supplements.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] The food industry is a major consumer of amino acids, especially glutamic acid, which is used as a flavor enhancer, and aspartame (aspartylphenylalanine 1-methyl ester), which is used as an artificial sweetener.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] Amino acids are sometimes added to food by manufacturers to alleviate symptoms of mineral deficiencies, such as anemia, by improving mineral absorption and reducing negative side effects from inorganic mineral supplementation.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] Amino acids are low-cost feedstocks used in chiral pool synthesis as enantiomerically pure building blocks.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] Amino acids are used in the synthesis of some cosmetics.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] The chelating ability of amino acids is sometimes used in fertilizers to facilitate the delivery of minerals to plants in order to correct mineral deficiencies, such as iron chlorosis.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] These fertilizers are also used to prevent deficiencies from occurring and to improve the overall health of the plants.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] Amino acids have been considered as components of biodegradable polymers, which have applications as environmentally friendly packaging and in medicine in drug delivery and the construction of prosthetic implants.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] An interesting example of such materials is polyaspartate, a water-soluble biodegradable polymer that may have applications in disposable diapers and agriculture.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] Due to its solubility and ability to chelate metal ions, polyaspartate is also being used as a biodegradable antiscaling agent and a corrosion inhibitor.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] The commercial production of amino acids usually relies on mutant bacteria that overproduce individual amino acids using glucose as a carbon source.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] Some amino acids are produced by enzymatic conversions of synthetic intermediates.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] 2-Aminothiazoline-4-carboxylic acid is an intermediate in one industrial synthesis of L-cysteine for example.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] Aspartic acid is produced by the addition of ammonia to fumarate using a lyase.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] In plants, nitrogen is first assimilated into organic compounds in the form of glutamate, formed from alpha-ketoglutarate and ammonia in the mitochondrion.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] For other amino acids, plants use transaminases to move the amino group from glutamate to another alpha-keto acid.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] For example, aspartate aminotransferase converts glutamate and oxaloacetate to alpha-ketoglutarate and aspartate.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] Other organisms use transaminases for amino acid synthesis, too.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] Nonstandard amino acids are usually formed through modifications to standard amino acids.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] For example, homocysteine is formed through the transsulfuration pathway or by the demethylation of methionine via the intermediate metabolite *S*-adenosylmethionine, while hydroxyproline is made by a post translational modification of proline.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] Microorganisms and plants synthesize many uncommon amino acids.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] For example, some microbes make 2-aminoisobutyric acid and lanthionine, which is a sulfide-bridged derivative of alanine.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] Both of these amino acids are found in peptidic lantibiotics such as alamethicin.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] However, in plants, 1-aminocyclopropane-1-carboxylic acid is a small disubstituted cyclic amino acid that is an intermediate in the production of the plant hormone ethylene.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] The formation of amino acids and peptides is assumed to have preceded and perhaps induced the emergence of life on earth.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] Amino acids can form from simple precursors under various conditions.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] Surface-based chemical metabolism of amino acids and very small compounds may have led to the build-up of amino acids, coenzymes and phosphate-based small carbon molecules.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] Amino acids and similar building blocks could have been elaborated into proto-peptides, with peptides being considered key players in the origin of life.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] In the famous Urey-Miller experiment, the passage of an electric arc through a mixture of methane, hydrogen, and ammonia produces a large number of amino acids.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] Several hypotheses invoke the Strecker synthesis whereby hydrogen cyanide, simple aldehydes, ammonia, and water produce amino acids.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] According to a review, amino acids, and even peptides, "turn up fairly regularly in the various experimental broths that have been allowed to be cooked from simple chemicals.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] This is because nucleotides are far more difficult to synthesize chemically than amino acids." For a chronological order, it suggests that there must have been a 'protein world' or at least a 'polypeptide world', possibly later followed by the 'RNA world' and the 'DNA world'.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] Codon–amino acids mappings may be the biological information system at the primordial origin of life on Earth.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] While amino acids and consequently simple peptides must have formed under different experimentally probed geochemical scenarios, the transition from an abiotic world to the first life forms is to a large extent still unresolved.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] Amino acids undergo the reactions expected of the constituent functional groups.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] As both the amine and carboxylic acid groups of amino acids can react to form amide bonds, one amino acid molecule can react with another and become joined through an amide linkage.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] This polymerization of amino acids is what creates proteins.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] This condensation reaction yields the newly formed peptide bond and a molecule of water.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] In cells, this reaction does not occur directly; instead, the amino acid is first activated by attachment to a transfer RNA molecule through an ester bond.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] This aminoacyl-tRNA is produced in an ATP-dependent reaction carried out by an aminoacyl tRNA synthetase.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] This aminoacyl-tRNA is then a substrate for the ribosome, which catalyzes the attack of the amino group of the elongating protein chain on the ester bond.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] As a result of this mechanism, all proteins made by ribosomes are synthesized starting at their *N*-terminus and moving toward their *C*-terminus.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] However, not all peptide bonds are formed in this way.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] In a few cases, peptides are synthesized by specific enzymes.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] For example, the tripeptide glutathione is an essential part of the defenses of cells against oxidative stress.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] This peptide is synthesized in two steps from free amino acids.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] In the first step, gamma-glutamylcysteine synthetase condenses cysteine and glutamate through a peptide bond formed between the side chain carboxyl of the glutamate (the gamma carbon of this side chain) and the amino group of the cysteine.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] This dipeptide is then condensed with glycine by glutathione synthetase to form glutathione.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] In chemistry, peptides are synthesized by a variety of reactions.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] One of the most-used in solid-phase peptide synthesis uses the aromatic oxime derivatives of amino acids as activated units.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] These are added in sequence onto the growing peptide chain, which is attached to a solid resin support.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] Libraries of peptides are used in drug discovery through high-throughput screening.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] The combination of functional groups allow amino acids to be effective polydentate ligands for metal–amino acid chelates.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] The side chains of amino acids can also undergo posttranslational chemical reactions.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] Degradation of an amino acid often begins with transamination, in which its amino group is transferred to α-ketoglutarate, forming glutamate.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] This process involves transaminases, often the same enzymes used in amino acid synthesis.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] In many vertebrates, the amino group is subsequently released as ammonia and converted to urea via the urea cycle for excretion.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] However, amino acid degradation can result in uric acid or ammonia instead, depending on the organism.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] For example, serine dehydratase converts serine directly to pyruvate and ammonia.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] Amino acids are bidentate ligands, forming transition metal amino acid complexes.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] The total nitrogen content of organic matter is mainly formed by the amino groups in proteins.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] The total Kjeldahl nitrogen (TKN) is a measure of nitrogen widely used in the analysis of (waste) water, soil, food, feed and organic matter in general.
[src:codon-reassignment/amino-acid] As the name suggests, the Kjeldahl method is applied.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] Like all animals, humans carry vast numbers (approximately 1013 to 1014) of bacteria.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] Most are in the gut, though there are many on the skin.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] Most of the bacteria in and on the body are harmless or rendered so by the protective effects of the immune system, and many are beneficial, particularly the ones in the gut.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] However, several species of bacteria are pathogenic and cause infectious diseases, including cholera, syphilis, anthrax, leprosy, tuberculosis, tetanus and bubonic plague.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] The most common fatal bacterial diseases are respiratory infections.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] Antibiotics are used to treat bacterial infections and are also used in farming, making antibiotic resistance a growing problem.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] Once regarded as plants constituting the class *Schizomycetes* ("fission fungi"), bacteria are now classified as prokaryotes.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] Unlike cells of animals and other eukaryotes, bacterial cells contain circular chromosomes, do not contain a nucleus and rarely harbour membrane-bound organelles.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] Although the term *bacteria* traditionally included all prokaryotes, the scientific classification changed after the discovery in the 1990s that prokaryotes consist of two very different groups of organisms that evolved from an ancient common ancestor.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] These evolutionary domains are called Bacteria and Archaea.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] Unlike Archaea, bacteria contain ester-linked lipids in the cell membrane, possess elongation factors that are resistant to ADP-ribosylation by diphtheria toxin, use formylmethionine in protein synthesis initiation, and have numerous genetic differences, including a different 16S rRNA.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] The word was first used to refer to bacteria in 1828.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] Although an estimated 43,000 species of bacteria have been named, most of them have never been studied.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] In fact, just 10 bacterial species account for half of all publications, whereas nearly 75% of all named bacteria have no academic research devoted to them.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] The best-studied species, *Escherichia coli*, has more than 300,000 studies published on it, but many of these papers likely use it only as a cloning vehicle to study other species, without providing any insight into its own biology.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] 90% of scientific studies on bacteria focus on less than 1% of species, mostly pathogenic bacteria relevant to human health.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] While *E. coli* is probably the best-studied bacterium, a quarter of its 4000 genes are poorly studied or remain uncharacterized.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] Some bacteria with minimal genomes (< 600 genes, e.g.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] *Mycoplasma*) usually have a large fraction of their genes functionally characterized, given that most of them are essential and conserved in many other species.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] The ancestors of bacteria were unicellular microorganisms that were the first forms of life to appear on Earth, about 4 billion years ago.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] For about 3 billion years, most organisms were microscopic, and bacteria and archaea were the dominant forms of life.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] Although bacterial fossils exist, such as stromatolites, their lack of distinctive morphology prevents them from being used to examine the history of bacterial evolution, or to date the time of origin of a particular bacterial species.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] However, gene sequences can be used to reconstruct the bacterial phylogeny, and these studies indicate that bacteria diverged first from the archaeal/eukaryotic lineage.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] The most recent common ancestor (MRCA) of bacteria and archaea was probably a hyperthermophile that lived about 2.5 billion–3.2 billion years ago.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] The earliest life on land may have been bacteria some 3.22 billion years ago.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] Bacteria were also involved in the second great evolutionary divergence, that of the archaea and eukaryotes.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] Here, eukaryotes resulted from the entering of ancient bacteria into endosymbiotic associations with the ancestors of eukaryotic cells, which were themselves possibly related to the Archaea.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] This involved the engulfment by proto-eukaryotic cells of alphaproteobacterial symbionts to form either mitochondria or hydrogenosomes, which are still found in all known Eukarya (sometimes in highly reduced form, e.g. in species of amitochondrial protozoa).
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] Later, some eukaryotes that already contained mitochondria also engulfed cyanobacteria-like organisms, leading to the formation of chloroplasts in algae and plants.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] Bacteria are ubiquitous, living in every possible habitat on the planet including soil, underwater, deep in Earth's crust and even such extreme environments as acidic hot springs and radioactive waste.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] There are thought to be approximately 2×1030 bacteria on Earth, forming a biomass that is only exceeded by plants.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] They are abundant in lakes and oceans, in arctic ice, and geothermal springs where they provide the nutrients needed to sustain life by converting dissolved compounds, such as hydrogen sulphide and methane, to energy.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] Most do not cause diseases, are beneficial to their environments, and are essential for life.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] The soil is a rich source of bacteria and a few grams contain around a thousand million of them.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] They are all essential to soil ecology, breaking down toxic waste and recycling nutrients.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] They are even found in the atmosphere and one cubic metre of air holds around one hundred million bacterial cells.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] The oceans and seas harbour around 3 × 1026 bacteria which provide up to 50% of the oxygen humans breathe.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] Only around 2% of bacterial species have been fully studied.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] Bacteria display a wide diversity of shapes and sizes.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] Bacterial cells are about one-tenth the size of eukaryotic cells and are typically 0.5–5.0 micrometres in length.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] However, a few species are visible to the unaided eye—for example, *Thiomargarita namibiensis* is up to half a millimetre long, *Epulopiscium fishelsoni* reaches 0.7 mm, and *Thiomargarita magnifica* can reach even 2 cm in length, which is 50 times larger than other known bacteria.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] Among the smallest bacteria are members of the genus *Mycoplasma*, which measure only 0.3 micrometres, as small as the largest viruses.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] Some bacteria may be even smaller, but these ultramicrobacteria are not well-studied.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] Most bacterial species are either spherical, called *cocci* (*singular coccus*, from Greek *kókkos*, grain, seed), or rod-shaped, called *bacilli* (*sing*. bacillus, from Latin *baculus*, stick).
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] Some bacteria, called *vibrio*, are shaped like slightly curved rods or comma-shaped; others can be spiral-shaped, called *spirilla*, or tightly coiled, called *spirochaetes*.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] A small number of other unusual shapes have been described, such as star-shaped bacteria.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] This wide variety of shapes is determined by the bacterial cell wall and cytoskeleton and is important because it can influence the ability of bacteria to acquire nutrients, attach to surfaces, swim through liquids and escape predators.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] Most bacterial species exist as single cells; others associate in characteristic patterns: *Neisseria* forms diploids (pairs), streptococci form chains, and staphylococci group together in "bunch of grapes" clusters.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] Bacteria can also group to form larger multicellular structures, such as the elongated filaments of *Actinomycetota* species, the aggregates of *Myxobacteria* species, and the complex hyphae of *Streptomyces* species.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] These multicellular structures are often only seen in certain conditions.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] For example, when starved of amino acids, myxobacteria detect surrounding cells in a process known as quorum sensing, migrate towards each other, and aggregate to form fruiting bodies up to 500 micrometres long and containing approximately 100,000 bacterial cells.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] In these fruiting bodies, the bacteria perform separate tasks; for example, about one in ten cells migrate to the top of a fruiting body and differentiate into a specialised dormant state called a myxospore, which is more resistant to drying and other adverse environmental conditions.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] Bacteria often attach to surfaces and form dense aggregations called biofilms and larger formations known as microbial mats.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] These biofilms and mats can range from a few micrometres in thickness to up to half a metre in depth, and may contain multiple species of bacteria, protists and archaea.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] Bacteria living in biofilms display a complex arrangement of cells and extracellular components, forming secondary structures, such as microcolonies, through which there are networks of channels to enable better diffusion of nutrients.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] In natural environments, such as soil or the surfaces of plants, the majority of bacteria are bound to surfaces in biofilms.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] Biofilms are also important in medicine, as these structures are often present during chronic bacterial infections or in infections of implanted medical devices, and bacteria protected within biofilms are much harder to kill than individual isolated bacteria.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] The bacterial cell is surrounded by a cell membrane, which is made primarily of phospholipids.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] This membrane encloses the contents of the cell and acts as a barrier to hold nutrients, proteins and other essential components within the cell.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] Unlike eukaryotic cells, bacteria usually lack large membrane-bound structures in their cytoplasm such as a nucleus, mitochondria, chloroplasts and the other organelles present in eukaryotic cells.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] However, some bacteria have protein-bound organelles in the cytoplasm which compartmentalise aspects of bacterial metabolism, such as the carboxysome.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] Additionally, bacteria have a multi-component cytoskeleton to control the localisation of proteins and nucleic acids within the cell, and to manage the process of cell division.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] Many important biochemical reactions, such as energy generation, occur due to differences in concentration of molecules across membranes, creating a electrochemical potential analogous to a battery.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] The general lack of internal membranes in bacteria means these reactions, such as electron transport, occur across the cell membrane between the cytoplasm and the outside of the cell or periplasm.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] However, in many photosynthetic bacteria, the plasma membrane is highly folded and fills most of the cell with layers of light-gathering membrane.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] These light-gathering complexes may even form lipid-enclosed structures called chlorosomes in green sulfur bacteria.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] Bacteria do not have a membrane-bound nucleus, and their genetic material is typically a single circular bacterial chromosome of DNA located in the cytoplasm in an irregularly shaped body called the nucleoid.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] The nucleoid contains the chromosome with its associated proteins and RNA.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] Like all other organisms, bacteria contain ribosomes for the production of proteins, but the structure of the bacterial ribosome is different from that of eukaryotes and archaea.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] Its translation process is also different.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] Some bacteria produce intracellular nutrient storage granules, such as glycogen, polyphosphate, sulfur or polyhydroxyalkanoates.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] Bacteria such as the photosynthetic cyanobacteria, produce internal gas vacuoles, which they use to regulate their buoyancy, allowing them to move up or down into water layers with different light intensities and nutrient levels.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] Around the outside of the cell membrane is the cell wall.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] Bacterial cell walls are made of peptidoglycan (also called murein), which is made from polysaccharide chains cross-linked by peptides containing D-amino acids.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] Bacterial cell walls are different from the cell walls of plants and fungi, which are made of cellulose and chitin, respectively.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] The cell wall of bacteria is also distinct from that of archaea, which do not contain peptidoglycan.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] The cell wall is essential to the survival of many bacteria, and the antibiotic penicillin (produced by a fungus called *Penicillium*) is able to kill bacteria by inhibiting a step in the synthesis of peptidoglycan.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] There are broadly speaking two different types of cell wall in bacteria, that classify bacteria into Gram-positive bacteria and Gram-negative bacteria.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] The names originate from the reaction of cells to the Gram stain, a long-standing test for the classification of bacterial species.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] Gram-positive bacteria possess a thick cell wall containing many layers of peptidoglycan and teichoic acids.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] In contrast, Gram-negative bacteria have a relatively thin cell wall consisting of a few layers of peptidoglycan surrounded by a second lipid membrane containing lipopolysaccharides and lipoproteins.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] Most bacteria have the Gram-negative cell wall, and only members of the *Bacillota* group and actinomycetota (previously known as the low G+C and high G+C Gram-positive bacteria, respectively) have the alternative Gram-positive arrangement.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] These differences in structure can produce differences in antibiotic susceptibility; for instance, vancomycin can kill only Gram-positive bacteria and is ineffective against Gram-negative pathogens, such as *Haemophilus influenzae* or *Pseudomonas aeruginosa*.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] Some bacteria have cell wall structures that are neither classically Gram-positive or Gram-negative.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] This includes clinically important bacteria such as mycobacteria which have a thick peptidoglycan cell wall like a Gram-positive bacterium, but also a second outer layer of lipids.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] In many bacteria, an S-layer of rigidly arrayed protein molecules covers the outside of the cell.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] This layer provides chemical and physical protection for the cell surface and can act as a macromolecular diffusion barrier.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] S-layers have diverse functions and are known to act as virulence factors in *Campylobacter* species and contain surface enzymes in *Bacillus stearothermophilus*.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] Flagella are rigid protein structures, about 20 nanometres in diameter and up to 20 micrometres in length, that are used for motility.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] Flagella are driven by the energy released by the transfer of ions down an electrochemical gradient across the cell membrane.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] Fimbriae (sometimes called "attachment pili") are fine filaments of protein, usually 2–10 nanometres in diameter and up to several micrometres in length.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] They are distributed over the surface of the cell, and resemble fine hairs when seen under the electron microscope.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] Fimbriae are believed to be involved in attachment to solid surfaces or to other cells, and are essential for the virulence of some bacterial pathogens.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] Pili (*sing*. pilus) are cellular appendages, slightly larger than fimbriae, that can transfer genetic material between bacterial cells in a process called conjugation where they are called conjugation pili or sex pili (see bacterial genetics, below).
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] They can also generate movement where they are called type IV pili.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] Glycocalyx is produced by many bacteria to surround their cells, and varies in structural complexity: ranging from a disorganised slime layer of extracellular polymeric substances to a highly structured capsule.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] These structures can protect cells from engulfment by eukaryotic cells such as macrophages (part of the human immune system).
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] They can also act as antigens and be involved in cell recognition, as well as aiding attachment to surfaces and the formation of biofilms.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] The assembly of these extracellular structures is dependent on bacterial secretion systems.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] These transfer proteins from the cytoplasm into the periplasm or into the environment around the cell.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] Many types of secretion systems are known and these structures are often essential for the virulence of pathogens, so are intensively studied.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] Some genera of Gram-positive bacteria, such as *Bacillus*, *Clostridium*, *Sporohalobacter*, *Anaerobacter*, and *Heliobacterium*, can form highly resistant, dormant structures called *endospores*.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] Endospores develop within the cytoplasm of the cell; generally, a single endospore develops in each cell.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] Each endospore contains a core of DNA and ribosomes surrounded by a cortex layer and protected by a multilayer rigid coat composed of peptidoglycan and a variety of proteins.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] Endospores show no detectable metabolism and can survive extreme physical and chemical stresses, such as high levels of UV light, gamma radiation, detergents, disinfectants, heat, freezing, pressure, and desiccation.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] In this dormant state, these organisms may remain viable for millions of years.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] Endospores even allow bacteria to survive exposure to the vacuum and radiation of outer space, leading to the possibility that bacteria could be distributed throughout the universe by space dust, meteoroids, asteroids, comets, planetoids, or directed panspermia.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] *Clostridioides difficile* infection, a common problem in healthcare settings, is caused by spore-forming bacteria.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] Bacteria exhibit an extremely wide variety of metabolic types.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] The distribution of metabolic traits within a group of bacteria has traditionally been used to define their taxonomy, but these traits often do not correspond with modern genetic classifications.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] Bacterial metabolism is classified into nutritional groups on the basis of three major criteria: the source of energy, the electron donors used, and the source of carbon used for growth.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] Phototrophic bacteria derive energy from light using photosynthesis, while chemotrophic bacteria breaking down chemical compounds through oxidation, driving metabolism by transferring electrons from a given electron donor to a terminal electron acceptor in a redox reaction.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] Chemotrophs are further divided by the types of compounds they use to transfer electrons.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] Bacteria that derive electrons from inorganic compounds such as hydrogen, carbon monoxide, or ammonia are called lithotrophs, while those that use organic compounds are called organotrophs.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] Still, more specifically, aerobic organisms use oxygen as the terminal electron acceptor, while anaerobic organisms use other compounds such as nitrate, sulfate, or carbon dioxide.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] Many bacteria, called heterotrophs, derive their carbon from other organic carbon.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] Others, such as cyanobacteria and some purple bacteria, are autotrophic, meaning they obtain cellular carbon by fixing carbon dioxide.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] In unusual circumstances, the gas methane can be used by methanotrophic bacteria as both a source of electrons and a substrate for carbon anabolism.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] In many ways, bacterial metabolism provides traits that are useful for ecological stability and for human society.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] For example, diazotrophs have the ability to fix nitrogen gas using the enzyme nitrogenase.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] This trait, which can be found in bacteria of most metabolic types listed above, leads to the ecologically important processes of denitrification, sulfate reduction, and acetogenesis, respectively.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] Bacterial metabolic processes are important drivers in biological responses to pollution; for example, sulfate-reducing bacteria are largely responsible for the production of the highly toxic forms of mercury (methyl- and dimethylmercury) in the environment.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] Nonrespiratory anaerobes use fermentation to generate energy and reducing power, secreting metabolic by-products (such as ethanol in brewing) as waste.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] Facultative anaerobes can switch between fermentation and different terminal electron acceptors depending on the environmental conditions in which they find themselves.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] Unlike in multicellular organisms, increases in cell size (cell growth) and reproduction by cell division are tightly linked in unicellular organisms.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] Bacteria grow to a fixed size and then reproduce through binary fission, a form of asexual reproduction.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] Under optimal conditions, bacteria can grow and divide extremely rapidly, and some bacterial populations can double as quickly as every 17 minutes.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] In cell division, two identical clone daughter cells are produced.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] Some bacteria, while still reproducing asexually, form more complex reproductive structures that help disperse the newly formed daughter cells.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] Examples include fruiting body formation by myxobacteria and aerial hyphae formation by *Streptomyces* species, or budding.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] Budding involves a cell forming a protrusion that breaks away and produces a daughter cell.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] In the laboratory, bacteria are usually grown using solid or liquid media.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] Solid growth media, such as agar plates, are used to isolate pure cultures of a bacterial strain.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] However, liquid growth media are used when the measurement of growth or large volumes of cells are required.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] Growth in stirred liquid media occurs as an even cell suspension, making the cultures easy to divide and transfer, although isolating single bacteria from liquid media is difficult.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] The use of selective media (media with specific nutrients added or deficient, or with antibiotics added) can help identify specific organisms.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] Most laboratory techniques for growing bacteria use high levels of nutrients to produce large amounts of cells cheaply and quickly.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] However, in natural environments, nutrients are limited, meaning that bacteria cannot continue to reproduce indefinitely.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] This nutrient limitation has led the evolution of different growth strategies (see r/K selection theory).
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] Some organisms can grow extremely rapidly when nutrients become available, such as the formation of algal and cyanobacterial blooms that often occur in lakes during the summer.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] Other organisms have adaptations to harsh environments, such as the production of multiple antibiotics by *Streptomyces* that inhibit the growth of competing microorganisms.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] In nature, many organisms live in communities (e.g., biofilms) that may allow for increased supply of nutrients and protection from environmental stresses.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] These relationships can be essential for growth of a particular organism or group of organisms (syntrophy).
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] When a population of bacteria first enter a high-nutrient environment that allows growth, the cells need to adapt to their new environment.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] The first phase of growth is the lag phase, a period of slow growth when the cells are adapting to the high-nutrient environment and preparing for fast growth.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] The lag phase has high biosynthesis rates, as proteins necessary for rapid growth are produced.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] The second phase of growth is the logarithmic phase, also known as the exponential phase.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] The log phase is marked by rapid exponential growth.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] The rate at which cells grow during this phase is known as the *growth rate* (*k*), and the time it takes the cells to double is known as the *generation time* (*g*).
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] During log phase, nutrients are metabolised at maximum speed until one of the nutrients is depleted and starts limiting growth.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] The third phase of growth is the *stationary phase* and is caused by depleted nutrients.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] The cells reduce their metabolic activity and consume non-essential cellular proteins.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] The stationary phase is a transition from rapid growth to a stress response state and there is increased expression of genes involved in DNA repair, antioxidant metabolism and nutrient transport.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] The final phase is the death phase where the bacteria run out of nutrients and die.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] There are many exceptions to this; for example, some *Streptomyces* and *Borrelia* species contain a single linear chromosome, while some bacteria including species of *Vibrio* contain more than one chromosome.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] Some bacteria contain plasmids, small extra-chromosomal molecules of DNA that may contain genes for various useful functions such as antibiotic resistance, metabolic capabilities, or various virulence factors.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] Whether they have a single chromosome or more than one, almost all bacteria have a haploid genome.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] This means that they have only one copy of each gene encoding proteins.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] This is in contrast to eukaryotes, which are diploid or polyploid, meaning they have two or more copies of each gene.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] This means that unlike humans, who may still be able to create a protein if the gene becomes mutated (since the human genome has an extra copy in each cell), a bacterium will be completely unable to create the protein if its gene incurs an inactivating mutation.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] Bacterial genomes usually encode a few hundred to a few thousand genes.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] The genes in bacterial genomes are usually a single continuous stretch of DNA.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] Although several different types of introns do exist in bacteria, these are much rarer than in eukaryotes.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] Bacteria, as asexual organisms, inherit an identical copy of the parent's genome and are clonal.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] However, all bacteria can evolve by selection on changes to their genetic material DNA caused by genetic recombination or mutations.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] Mutations arise from errors made during the replication of DNA or from exposure to mutagens.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] Mutation rates vary widely among different species of bacteria and even among different clones of a single species of bacteria.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] Genetic changes in bacterial genomes emerge from either random mutation during replication or "stress-directed mutation", where genes involved in a particular growth-limiting process have an increased mutation rate.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] Some bacteria transfer genetic material between cells.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] First, bacteria can take up exogenous DNA from their environment in a process called transformation.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] Many bacteria can naturally take up DNA from the environment, while others must be chemically altered in order to induce them to take up DNA.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] The development of competence in nature is usually associated with stressful environmental conditions and seems to be an adaptation for facilitating repair of DNA damage in recipient cells.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] Second, bacteriophages can integrate into the bacterial chromosome, introducing foreign DNA in a process known as transduction.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] Many types of bacteriophage exist; some infect and lyse their host bacteria, while others insert into the bacterial chromosome.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] Third, bacteria can transfer genetic material through direct cell contact via conjugation.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] In such cases, gene acquisition from other bacteria or the environment is called horizontal gene transfer and may be common under natural conditions.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] Many bacteria are motile (able to move themselves) and do so using a variety of mechanisms.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] The best studied of these are flagella, long filaments that are turned by a motor at the base to generate propeller-like movement.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] The bacterial flagellum is made of about 20 proteins, with approximately another 30 proteins required for its regulation and assembly.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] The flagellum is a rotating structure driven by a reversible motor at the base that uses the electrochemical gradient across the membrane for power.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] Bacteria can use flagella in different ways to generate different kinds of movement.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] Many bacteria (such as *E. coli*) have two distinct modes of movement: forward movement (swimming) and tumbling.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] The tumbling allows them to reorient and makes their movement a three-dimensional random walk.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] The flagella of a group of bacteria, the spirochaetes, are found between two membranes in the periplasmic space.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] They have a distinctive helical body that twists about as it moves.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] Two other types of bacterial motion are called twitching motility that relies on a structure called the type IV pilus, and gliding motility, that uses other mechanisms.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] In twitching motility, the rod-like pilus extends out from the cell, binds some substrate, and then retracts, pulling the cell forward.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] Motile bacteria are attracted or repelled by certain stimuli in behaviours called *taxes*: these include chemotaxis, phototaxis, energy taxis, and magnetotaxis.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] In one peculiar group, the myxobacteria, individual bacteria move together to form waves of cells that then differentiate to form fruiting bodies containing spores.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] The myxobacteria move only when on solid surfaces, unlike *E. coli*, which is motile in liquid or solid media.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] Several *Listeria* and *Shigella* species move inside host cells by usurping the cytoskeleton, which is normally used to move organelles inside the cell.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] By promoting actin polymerisation at one pole of their cells, they can form a kind of tail that pushes them through the host cell's cytoplasm.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] A few bacteria have chemical systems that generate light.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] This bioluminescence often occurs in bacteria that live in association with fish, and the light probably serves to attract fish or other large animals.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] Bacteria often function as multicellular aggregates known as biofilms, exchanging a variety of molecular signals for intercell communication and engaging in coordinated multicellular behaviour.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] The communal benefits of multicellular cooperation include a cellular division of labour, accessing resources that cannot effectively be used by single cells, collectively defending against antagonists, and optimising population survival by differentiating into distinct cell types.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] For example, bacteria in biofilms can have more than five hundred times the increased resistance to antibacterial agents than individual "planktonic" bacteria of the same species.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] One type of intercellular communication by a molecular signal is called quorum sensing.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] Quorum sensing determines whether the local population is dense enough to support investment in processes that are only successful if large numbers of similar organisms behave similarly, such as excreting digestive enzymes or emitting light.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] Quorum sensing enables bacteria to coordinate gene expression and to produce, release, and detect autoinducers or pheromones that accumulate with the growth in cell population.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] Classification seeks to describe the diversity of bacterial species by naming and grouping organisms based on similarities.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] Bacteria can be classified on the basis of cell structure, cellular metabolism or on differences in cell components, such as DNA, fatty acids, pigments, antigens and quinones.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] While these schemes allowed the identification and classification of **bacterial strains**, it was unclear whether these differences represented variation between distinct species or between strains of the same species.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] This uncertainty was due to the lack of distinctive structures in most bacteria, as well as lateral gene transfer between unrelated species.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] Due to lateral gene transfer, some closely related bacteria can have very different morphologies and metabolisms.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] Classification of bacteria is determined by publication in the International Journal of Systematic Bacteriology, and Bergey's Manual of Systematic Bacteriology.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] The International Committee on Systematic Bacteriology (ICSB) maintains international rules for the naming of bacteria and taxonomic categories and for the ranking of them in the International Code of Nomenclature of Bacteria.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] Historically, bacteria were considered a part of the Plantae, the plant kingdom, and were called "Schizomycetes" (fission-fungi).
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] For this reason, collective bacteria and other microorganisms in a host are often called "flora".
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] The term "bacteria" was traditionally applied to all microscopic, single-cell prokaryotes.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] However, molecular systematics showed prokaryotic life to consist of two separate domains, originally called Eubacteria and Archaebacteria, but now called Bacteria and Archaea that evolved independently from an ancient common ancestor.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] The archaea and eukaryotes are more closely related to each other than either is to the bacteria.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] These two domains, along with Eukarya, are the basis of the three-domain system, which is currently the most widely used classification system in microbiology.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] However, due to the relatively recent introduction of molecular systematics and a rapid increase in the number of genome sequences that are available, bacterial classification remains a changing and expanding field.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] For example, Cavalier-Smith argued that the Archaea and Eukaryotes evolved from Gram-positive bacteria.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] The identification of bacteria in the laboratory is particularly relevant in medicine, where the correct treatment is determined by the bacterial species causing an infection.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] Consequently, the need to identify human pathogens was a major impetus for the development of techniques to identify bacteria.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] Once a pathogenic organism has been isolated, it can be further characterised by its morphology, growth patterns (such as aerobic or anaerobic growth), patterns of hemolysis, and staining.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] The *Gram stain*, developed in 1884 by Hans Christian Gram, characterises bacteria based on the structural characteristics of their cell walls.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] The thick layers of peptidoglycan in the "Gram-positive" cell wall stain purple, while the thin "Gram-negative" cell wall appears pink.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] By combining morphology and Gram-staining, most bacteria can be classified as belonging to one of four groups (Gram-positive cocci, Gram-positive bacilli, Gram-negative cocci and Gram-negative bacilli).
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] Some organisms are best identified by stains other than the Gram stain, particularly mycobacteria or *Nocardia*, which show acid fastness on Ziehl–Neelsen or similar stains.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] Culture techniques are designed to promote the growth and identify particular bacteria while restricting the growth of the other bacteria in the sample.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] Often these techniques are designed for specific specimens; for example, a sputum sample will be treated to identify organisms that cause pneumonia, while stool specimens are cultured on selective media to identify organisms that cause diarrhea while preventing growth of non-pathogenic bacteria.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] Specimens that are normally sterile, such as blood, urine or spinal fluid, are cultured under conditions designed to grow all possible organisms.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] Other organisms may need to be identified by their growth in special media, or by other techniques, such as serology.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] As with bacterial classification, identification of bacteria is increasingly using molecular methods, and mass spectroscopy.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] Most bacteria have not been characterised and there are many species that cannot be grown in the laboratory.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] Diagnostics using DNA-based tools, such as polymerase chain reaction, are increasingly popular due to their specificity and speed, compared to culture-based methods.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] These methods also allow the detection and identification of "viable but nonculturable" cells that are metabolically active but non-dividing.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] The main way to characterize and classify these bacteria is to isolate their DNA from environmental samples and mass-sequence them.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] This approach has identified thousands, if not millions of candidate species.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p01] Based on some estimates, more than 43,000 species of bacteria have been described, but attempts to estimate the true number of bacterial diversity have ranged from 107 to 109 total species—and even these diverse estimates may be off by many orders of magnitude.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p02] Despite their apparent simplicity, bacteria can form complex associations with other organisms.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p02] These symbiotic associations can be divided into parasitism, mutualism and commensalism.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p02] The word "commensalism" is derived from the word "commensal", meaning "eating at the same table" and all plants and animals are colonised by commensal bacteria.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p02] In humans and other animals, trillions of them live on the skin, the airways, the gut and other orifices.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p02] Referred to as "normal flora", or "commensals", these bacteria usually cause no harm but may occasionally invade other sites of the body and cause infection.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p02] *Escherichia coli* is a commensal in the human gut but can cause urinary tract infections.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p02] Similarly, streptococci, which are part of the normal flora of the human mouth, can cause heart disease.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p02] Some species of bacteria kill and then consume other microorganisms; these species are called *predatory bacteria*.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p02] These include organisms such as *Myxococcus xanthus*, which forms swarms of cells that kill and digest any bacteria they encounter.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p02] Other bacterial predators either attach to their prey in order to digest them and absorb nutrients or invade another cell and multiply inside the cytosol.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p02] These predatory bacteria are thought to have evolved from saprophages that consumed dead microorganisms, through adaptations that allowed them to entrap and kill other organisms.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p02] Certain bacteria form close spatial associations that are essential for their survival.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p02] One such mutualistic association, called interspecies hydrogen transfer, occurs between clusters of anaerobic bacteria that consume organic acids, such as butyric acid or propionic acid, and produce hydrogen, and methanogenic archaea that consume hydrogen.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p02] The bacteria in this association are unable to consume the organic acids as this reaction produces hydrogen that accumulates in their surroundings.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p02] Only the intimate association with the hydrogen-consuming archaea keeps the hydrogen concentration low enough to allow the bacteria to grow.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p02] In soil, microorganisms that reside in the rhizosphere (a zone that includes the root surface and the soil that adheres to the root after gentle shaking) carry out nitrogen fixation, converting nitrogen gas to nitrogenous compounds.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p02] This serves to provide an easily absorbable form of nitrogen for many plants, which cannot fix nitrogen themselves.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p02] Many other bacteria are found as symbionts in humans and other organisms.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p02] The presence of this gut flora also inhibits the growth of potentially pathogenic bacteria (usually through competitive exclusion) and these beneficial bacteria are consequently sold as probiotic dietary supplements.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p02] Nearly all animal life is dependent on bacteria for survival as only bacteria and some archaea possess the genes and enzymes necessary to synthesise vitamin B12, also known as cobalamin, and provide it through the food chain.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p02] Vitamin B12 is a water-soluble vitamin that is involved in the metabolism of every cell of the human body.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p02] It is a cofactor in DNA synthesis and in both fatty acid and amino acid metabolism.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p02] It is particularly important in the normal functioning of the nervous system via its role in the synthesis of myelin.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p02] The body is continually exposed to many species of bacteria, including beneficial commensals, which grow on the skin and mucous membranes, and saprophytes, which grow mainly in the soil and in decaying matter.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p02] The blood and tissue fluids contain nutrients sufficient to sustain the growth of many bacteria.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p02] The body has defence mechanisms that enable it to resist microbial invasion of its tissues and give it a natural immunity or innate resistance against many microorganisms.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p02] Unlike some viruses, bacteria evolve relatively slowly so many bacterial diseases also occur in other animals.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p02] If bacteria form a parasitic association with other organisms, they are classed as pathogens.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p02] A pathogenic cause for a known medical disease may only be discovered many years later, as was the case with *Helicobacter pylori* and peptic ulcer disease.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p02] Bacterial diseases are also important in agriculture, and bacteria cause leaf spot, fire blight and wilts in plants, as well as Johne's disease, mastitis, salmonella and anthrax in farm animals.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p02] Each species of pathogen has a characteristic spectrum of interactions with its human hosts.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p02] Some organisms, such as *Staphylococcus* or *Streptococcus*, can cause skin infections, pneumonia, meningitis and sepsis, a systemic inflammatory response producing shock, massive vasodilation and death.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p02] Yet these organisms are also part of the normal human flora and usually exist on the skin or in the nose without causing any disease at all.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p02] Other organisms invariably cause disease in humans, such as *Rickettsia*, which are obligate intracellular parasites able to grow and reproduce only within the cells of other organisms.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p02] One species of *Rickettsia* causes typhus, while another causes Rocky Mountain spotted fever.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p02] *Chlamydia*, another phylum of obligate intracellular parasites, contains species that can cause pneumonia or urinary tract infection and may be involved in coronary heart disease.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p02] Some species, such as *Pseudomonas aeruginosa*, *Burkholderia cenocepacia*, and *Mycobacterium avium*, are opportunistic pathogens and cause disease mainly in people who are immunosuppressed or have cystic fibrosis.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p02] Some bacteria produce toxins, which cause diseases.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p02] These are endotoxins, which come from broken bacterial cells, and exotoxins, which are produced by bacteria and released into the environment.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p02] The bacterium *Clostridium botulinum* for example, produces a powerful exotoxin that cause respiratory paralysis, and *Salmonellae* produce an endotoxin that causes gastroenteritis.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p02] Some exotoxins can be converted to toxoids, which are used as vaccines to prevent the disease.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p02] Bacterial infections may be treated with antibiotics, which are classified as bacteriocidal if they kill bacteria or bacteriostatic if they just prevent bacterial growth.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p02] There are many types of antibiotics, and each class inhibits a process that is different in the pathogen from that found in the host.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p02] An example of how antibiotics produce selective toxicity are chloramphenicol and puromycin, which inhibit the bacterial ribosome, but not the structurally different eukaryotic ribosome.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p02] Antibiotics are used both in treating human disease and in intensive farming to promote animal growth, where they may be contributing to the rapid development of antibiotic resistance in bacterial populations.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p02] Infections can be prevented by antiseptic measures such as sterilising the skin prior to piercing it with the needle of a syringe, and by proper care of indwelling catheters.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p02] Surgical and dental instruments are also sterilised to prevent contamination by bacteria.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p02] Disinfectants such as bleach are used to kill bacteria or other pathogens on surfaces to prevent contamination and further reduce the risk of infection.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p02] Bacteria, often lactic acid bacteria, such as *Lactobacillus* species and *Lactococcus* species, in combination with yeasts and moulds, have been used for thousands of years in the preparation of fermented foods, such as cheese, pickles, soy sauce, sauerkraut, vinegar, wine, and yogurt.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p02] The ability of bacteria to degrade a variety of organic compounds is remarkable and has been used in waste processing and bioremediation.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p02] Bacteria capable of digesting the hydrocarbons in petroleum are often used to clean up oil spills.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p02] Fertiliser was added to some of the beaches in Prince William Sound in an attempt to promote the growth of these naturally occurring bacteria after the 1989 *Exxon Valdez* oil spill.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p02] These efforts were effective on beaches that were not too thickly covered in oil.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p02] Bacteria are also used for the bioremediation of industrial toxic wastes.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p02] In the chemical industry, bacteria are most important in the production of enantiomerically pure chemicals for use as pharmaceuticals or agrichemicals.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p02] Bacteria can also be used in place of pesticides in biological pest control.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p02] This commonly involves *Bacillus thuringiensis* (also called BT), a Gram-positive, soil-dwelling bacterium.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p02] Subspecies of this bacteria are used as Lepidopteran-specific insecticides under trade names such as Dipel and Thuricide.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p02] Because of their specificity, these pesticides are regarded as environmentally friendly, with little or no effect on humans, wildlife, pollinators, and most other beneficial insects.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p02] Because of their ability to quickly grow and the relative ease with which they can be manipulated, bacteria are the workhorses for the fields of molecular biology, genetics, and biochemistry.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p02] By making mutations in bacterial DNA and examining the resulting phenotypes, scientists can determine the function of genes, enzymes, and metabolic pathways in bacteria, then apply this knowledge to more complex organisms.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p02] This aim of understanding the biochemistry of a cell reaches its most complex expression in the synthesis of huge amounts of enzyme kinetic and gene expression data into mathematical models of entire organisms.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p02] This is achievable in some well-studied bacteria, with models of *Escherichia coli* metabolism now being produced and tested.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p02] This understanding of bacterial metabolism and genetics allows the use of biotechnology to bioengineer bacteria for the production of therapeutic proteins, such as insulin, growth factors, or antibodies.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p02] Because of their importance for research in general, samples of bacterial strains are isolated and preserved in Biological Resource Centres.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p02] This ensures the availability of the strain to scientists worldwide.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p02] Bacteria were first observed by the Dutch microscopist Antonie van Leeuwenhoek in 1676, using a single-lens microscope of his own design.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p02] Leeuwenhoek did not recognize bacteria as a distinct category of microorganisms, referring to all microorganisms that he observed, including bacteria, protists, and microscopic animals, as animalcules.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p02] He published his observations in a series of letters to the Royal Society of London.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p02] Bacteria were Leeuwenhoek's most remarkable microscopic discovery.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p02] Their size was just at the limit of what his simple lenses could resolve, and, in one of the most striking hiatuses in the history of science, no one else would see them again for over a century.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p02] His observations also included protozoans, and his findings were looked at again in the light of the more recent findings of cell theory.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p02] Christian Gottfried Ehrenberg introduced the word "bacterium" in 1828.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p02] In fact, his *Bacterium* was a genus that contained non-spore-forming rod-shaped bacteria, as opposed to *Bacillus*, a genus of spore-forming rod-shaped bacteria defined by Ehrenberg in 1835.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p02] Louis Pasteur demonstrated in 1859 that the growth of microorganisms causes the fermentation process and that this growth is not due to spontaneous generation (yeasts and molds, commonly associated with fermentation, are not bacteria, but rather fungi).
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p02] Along with his contemporary Robert Koch, Pasteur was an early advocate of the germ theory of disease.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p02] Before them, Ignaz Semmelweis and Joseph Lister had realised the importance of sanitised hands in medical work.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p02] Semmelweis, who in the 1840s formulated his rules for handwashing in the hospital, prior to the advent of germ theory, attributed disease to "decomposing animal organic matter".
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p02] His ideas were rejected and his book on the topic condemned by the medical community.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p02] After Lister, however, doctors started sanitising their hands in the 1870s.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p02] Robert Koch, a pioneer in medical microbiology, worked on cholera, anthrax and tuberculosis.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p02] In his research into tuberculosis, Koch finally proved the germ theory, for which he received a Nobel Prize in 1905.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p02] In Koch's postulates, he set out criteria to test if an organism is the cause of a disease, and these postulates are still used today.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p02] Ferdinand Cohn is said to be a founder of bacteriology, studying bacteria from 1870.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p02] Cohn was the first to classify bacteria based on their morphology.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p02] Though it was known in the nineteenth century that bacteria are the cause of many diseases, no effective antibacterial treatments were available.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p02] In 1910, Paul Ehrlich developed the first antibiotic, by changing dyes that selectively stained *Treponema pallidum*—the spirochaete that causes syphilis—into compounds that selectively killed the pathogen.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p02] Ehrlich, who had been awarded a 1908 Nobel Prize for his work on immunology, pioneered the use of stains to detect and identify bacteria, with his work being the basis of the Gram stain and the Ziehl–Neelsen stain.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p02] A major step forward in the study of bacteria came in 1977 when Carl Woese recognised that archaea have a separate line of evolutionary descent from bacteria.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteria-p02] This new phylogenetic taxonomy depended on the sequencing of 16S ribosomal RNA and divided prokaryotes into two evolutionary domains, as part of the three-domain system.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] A **bacteriophage** (/bækˈtɪrioʊfeɪdʒ/), also known informally as a **phage** (/ˈfeɪdʒ/), is a virus that infects and replicates within bacteria.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] The term is derived from Ancient Greek φαγεῖν*(phagein)* 'to devour' and *bacteria*.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] Bacteriophages are composed of proteins that encapsulate a DNA or RNA genome, and may have structures that are either simple or elaborate.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] Their genomes may encode as few as four genes (e.g.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] Phages replicate within the bacterium following the injection of their genome into its cytoplasm.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] Bacteriophages are among the most common and diverse entities in the biosphere.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] Bacteriophages are ubiquitous viruses, found wherever bacteria exist.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] It is estimated there are more than 1031 bacteriophages on the planet, more than every living organism on Earth, including bacteria, combined.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] Bacteriophages were used from the 1920s as an alternative to antibiotics in the Soviet Union and Central Europe, as well as in France and Brazil.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] They are seen as a possible therapy against multi-drug-resistant strains of many bacteria.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] Bacteriophages are known to interact with the immune system both indirectly via bacterial expression of phage-encoded proteins and directly by influencing innate immunity and bacterial clearance.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] Phage–host interactions are becoming increasingly important areas of research.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] In 1896, Ernest Hanbury Hankin reported that something in the waters of the Ganges and Yamuna rivers in India had a marked antibacterial action against cholera and it could pass through a very fine porcelain Chamberland filter.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] In 1915, British bacteriologist Frederick Twort, superintendent of the Brown Institution of London, discovered a small agent that infected and killed bacteria.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] Twort's research was interrupted by the onset of World War I, as well as a shortage of funding and the discoveries of antibiotics.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] Independently, French-Canadian microbiologist Félix d'Hérelle, working at the Pasteur Institute in Paris, announced on 3 September 1917 that he had discovered "an invisible, antagonistic microbe of the dysentery bacillus".
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] He also recorded a dramatic account of a man suffering from dysentery who was restored to good health by the bacteriophages.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] It was d'Hérelle who conducted much research into bacteriophages and introduced the concept of phage therapy.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] In 1919, in Paris, France, d'Hérelle conducted the first clinical application of a bacteriophage, with the first reported use in the United States being in 1922.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] In 1969, Max Delbrück, Alfred Hershey, and Salvador Luria were awarded the Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine for their discoveries of the replication of viruses and their genetic structure.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] Specifically the work of Hershey, as contributor to the Hershey–Chase experiment in 1952, provided convincing evidence that DNA, not protein, was the genetic material of life.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] Delbrück and Luria carried out the Luria–Delbrück experiment which demonstrated statistically that mutations in bacteria occur randomly and thus follow Darwinian rather than Lamarckian principles.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] In 2018, George Smith and Gregory Winter were awarded Nobel Prize in Chemistry for the phage display of peptides and antibodies.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] Phages were discovered to be antibacterial agents and were used in the former Soviet Republic of Georgia (pioneered there by Giorgi Eliava with help from the co-discoverer of bacteriophages, Félix d'Hérelle) during the 1920s and 1930s for treating bacterial infections.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] They had widespread use, including treatment of soldiers in the Red Army.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] The use of phages has continued since the end of the Cold War in Russia, Georgia, and elsewhere in Central and Eastern Europe.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] The first regulated, randomized, double-blind clinical trial was reported in the *Journal of Wound Care* in June 2009, which evaluated the safety and efficacy of a bacteriophage cocktail to treat infected venous ulcers of the leg in human patients.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] The FDA approved the study as a Phase I clinical trial.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] The study's results demonstrated the safety of therapeutic application of bacteriophages, but did not show efficacy.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] The authors explained that the use of certain chemicals that are part of standard wound care (e.g. lactoferrin or silver) may have interfered with bacteriophage viability.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] Shortly after that, another controlled clinical trial in Western Europe (treatment of ear infections caused by *Pseudomonas aeruginosa*) was reported in the journal *Clinical Otolaryngology* in August 2009.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] The study concludes that bacteriophage preparations were safe and effective for treatment of chronic ear infections in humans.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] Additionally, there have been numerous animal and other experimental clinical trials evaluating the efficacy of bacteriophages for various diseases, such as infected burns and wounds, and cystic fibrosis-associated lung infections, among others.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] On the other hand, phages of *Inoviridae* have been shown to complicate biofilms involved in pneumonia and cystic fibrosis and to shelter the bacteria from drugs meant to eradicate disease, thus promoting persistent infection.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] Meanwhile, bacteriophage researchers have been developing engineered viruses to overcome antibiotic resistance, and engineering the phage genes responsible for coding enzymes that degrade the biofilm matrix, phage structural proteins, and the enzymes responsible for lysis of the bacterial cell wall.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] There have been results showing that T4 phages that are small in size and short-tailed can be helpful in detecting *E. coli* in the human body.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] Therapeutic efficacy of a phage cocktail was evaluated in a mouse model with nasal infection of multi-drug-resistant (MDR) *A. baumannii*.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] Mice treated with the phage cocktail showed a 2.3-fold higher survival rate compared to those untreated at seven days post-infection.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] In 2017, a 68-year-old diabetic patient with necrotizing pancreatitis complicated by a pseudocyst infected with MDR *A. baumannii* strains was being treated with a cocktail of Azithromycin, Rifampicin, and Colistin for 4 months without results and overall rapidly declining health.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] Once on the combination of the IV and PC therapy the patient's downward clinical trajectory reversed, and within two days he had awoken from his coma and become responsive.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] As his immune system began to function he had to be temporarily removed from the cocktail because his fever was spiking to over 104 °F (40 °C), but after two days the phage cocktails were re-introduced at levels he was able to tolerate.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] The original three-antibiotic cocktail was replaced by minocycline after the bacterial strain was found not to be resistant to this and he rapidly regained full lucidity, although he was not discharged from the hospital until roughly 145 days after phage therapy began.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] Phages have increasingly been used to safen food products and to forestall spoilage bacteria.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] Since 2006, the United States Food and Drug Administration (FDA) and United States Department of Agriculture (USDA) have approved several bacteriophage products.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] LMP-102 (Intralytix) was approved for treating ready-to-eat (RTE) poultry and meat products.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] In that same year, the FDA approved LISTEX (developed and produced by Micreos) using bacteriophages on cheese to kill *Listeria monocytogenes* bacteria, in order to give them generally recognized as safe (GRAS) status.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] In July 2007, the same bacteriophage were approved for use on all food products.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] In 2011 USDA confirmed that LISTEX is a clean label processing aid and is included in USDA.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] Research in the field of food safety is continuing to see if lytic phages are a viable option to control other food-borne pathogens in various food products.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] Switzerland authorized a phage for use in cheese production in 2016.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] The European Union has not yet (2025) authorized any.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] Bacteriophages, including those specific to *Escherichia coli*, have been employed as indicators of fecal contamination in water sources.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] Due to their shared structural and biological characteristics, coliphages can serve as proxies for viral fecal contamination and the presence of pathogenic viruses such as rotavirus, norovirus, and HAV.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] Research conducted on wastewater treatment systems has revealed significant disparities in the behavior of coliphages compared to fecal coliforms, demonstrating a distinct correlation with the recovery of pathogenic viruses at the treatment's conclusion.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] Establishing a secure discharge threshold, studies have determined that discharges below 3000 PFU/100 mL are considered safe in terms of limiting the release of pathogenic viruses.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] In 2011, the FDA cleared the first bacteriophage-based product for in vitro diagnostic use.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] The KeyPath MRSA/MSSA Blood Culture Test uses a cocktail of bacteriophage to detect *Staphylococcus aureus* in positive blood cultures and determine methicillin resistance or susceptibility.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] The test returns results in about five hours, compared to two to three days for standard microbial identification and susceptibility test methods.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] It was the first accelerated antibiotic-susceptibility test approved by the FDA.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] Government agencies in the West have for several years been looking to Georgia and the former Soviet Union for help with exploiting phages for counteracting bioweapons and toxins, such as anthrax and botulism.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] Developments are continuing among research groups in the U.S.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] Other uses include spray application in horticulture for protecting plants and vegetable produce from decay and the spread of bacterial disease.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] Other applications for bacteriophages are as biocides for environmental surfaces, e.g., in hospitals, and as preventative treatments for catheters and medical devices before use in clinical settings.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] The technology for phages to be applied to dry surfaces, e.g., uniforms, curtains, or even sutures for surgery now exists.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] Clinical trials reported in *Clinical Otolaryngology* show success in veterinary treatment of pet dogs with otitis.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] The sensing of phage-triggered ion cascades (SEPTIC) bacterium sensing and identification method uses the ion emission and its dynamics during phage infection and offers high specificity and speed for detection.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] Phage display is a different use of phages involving a library of phages with a variable peptide linked to a surface protein.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] Each phage genome encodes the variant of the protein displayed on its surface (hence the name), providing a link between the peptide variant and its encoding gene.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] Variant phages from the library may be selected through their binding affinity to an immobilized molecule (e.g., botulism toxin) to neutralize it.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] The bound, selected phages can be multiplied by reinfecting a susceptible bacterial strain, thus allowing them to retrieve the peptides encoded in them for further study.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] Phage proteins often have antimicrobial activity and may serve as leads for peptidomimetics, i.e. drugs that mimic peptides.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] Phage-ligand technology makes use of phage proteins for various applications, such as binding of bacteria and bacterial components (e.g. endotoxin) and lysis of bacteria.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] Bacteriophages are important model organisms for studying principles of evolution and ecology.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] Phages can be used to combat bacterial infections such as blackleg.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] A line of phage-based products is licensed in the United States, and Georgia has long used agricultural phages.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] Elsewhere, research and pilot testing are still underway.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] This is notably the case in Switzerland, where research is being conducted by the Fribourg School of Engineering and Architecture in collaboration with the Lausanne University Hospital (CHUV).
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] Bacteriophages present in the environment can cause cheese to not ferment.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] In order to avoid this, mixed-strain starter cultures and culture rotation regimes can be used.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] Genetic engineering of culture microbes – especially *Lactococcus lactis* and *Streptococcus thermophilus* – have been studied for genetic analysis and modification to improve phage resistance.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] This has especially focused on plasmid and recombinant chromosomal modifications.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] Some research has focused on the potential of bacteriophages as antimicrobial against foodborne pathogens and biofilm formation within the dairy industry.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] As the spread of antibiotic resistance is a main concern within the dairy industry, phages can serve as a promising alternative.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] The life cycle of bacteriophages tends to be either a lytic cycle or a lysogenic cycle.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] In addition, some phages display pseudolysogenic behaviors.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] With *lytic phages* such as the T4 phage, bacterial cells are broken open (lysed) and destroyed after immediate replication of the virion.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] As soon as the cell is destroyed, the phage progeny can find new hosts to infect.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] Lytic phages are more suitable for phage therapy.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] Some lytic phages undergo a phenomenon known as lysis inhibition, where completed phage progeny will not immediately lyse out of the cell if extracellular phage concentrations are high.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] This mechanism is not identical to that of the temperate phage going dormant and usually is temporary.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] In contrast, the *lysogenic cycle* does not result in immediate lysing of the host cell.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] Those phages able to undergo lysogeny are known as temperate phages.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] Their viral genome will integrate with host DNA and replicate along with it, relatively harmlessly, or may even become established as a plasmid.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] The virus remains dormant until host conditions deteriorate, perhaps due to depletion of nutrients, then, the endogenous phages (known as prophages) become active.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] At this point they initiate the reproductive cycle, resulting in lysis of the host cell.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] As the lysogenic cycle allows the host cell to continue to survive and reproduce, the virus is replicated in all offspring of the cell.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] Sometimes prophages may provide benefits to the host bacterium while they are dormant by adding new functions to the bacterial genome, in a phenomenon called lysogenic conversion.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] Examples are the conversion of harmless strains of *Corynebacterium diphtheriae* or *Vibrio cholerae* by bacteriophages to highly virulent ones that cause diphtheria or cholera, respectively.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] Strategies to combat certain bacterial infections by targeting these toxin-encoding prophages have been proposed.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] Bacterial cells are protected by a cell wall of polysaccharides, which are important virulence factors protecting bacterial cells against both immune host defenses and antibiotics.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] To enter a host cell, bacteriophages bind to specific receptors on the surface of bacteria, including lipopolysaccharides, teichoic acids, proteins, or even flagella.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] This specificity means a bacteriophage can infect only certain bacteria bearing receptors to which they can bind, which in turn, determines the phage's host range.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] Polysaccharide-degrading enzymes are virion-associated proteins that enzymatically degrade the capsular outer layer of their hosts at the initial step of a tightly programmed phage infection process.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] Host growth conditions also influence the ability of the phage to attach and invade them.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] As phage virions do not move independently, they must rely on random encounters with the correct receptors when in solution, such as blood, lymphatic circulation, irrigation, soil water, etc.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] Myovirus bacteriophages use a hypodermic syringe-like motion to inject their genetic material into the cell.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] After contacting the appropriate receptor, the tail fibers flex to bring the base plate closer to the surface of the cell.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] Once attached completely, irreversible binding is initiated and the tail contracts, possibly with the help of ATP present in the tail, injecting genetic material through the bacterial membrane.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] The injection is accomplished through a sort of bending motion in the shaft by going to the side, contracting closer to the cell and pushing back up.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] Podoviruses lack an elongated tail sheath like that of a myovirus, so instead, they use their small, tooth-like tail fibers enzymatically to degrade a portion of the cell membrane before inserting their genetic material.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] Within minutes, bacterial ribosomes start translating viral mRNA into protein.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] For RNA-based phages, RNA replicase is synthesized early in the process.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] Proteins modify the bacterial RNA polymerase so it preferentially transcribes viral mRNA.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] The host's normal synthesis of proteins and nucleic acids is disrupted, and it is forced to manufacture viral products instead.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] These products go on to become part of new virions within the cell, helper proteins that contribute to the assemblage of new virions, or proteins involved in cell lysis.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] In 1972, Walter Fiers (University of Ghent, Belgium) was the first to establish the complete nucleotide sequence of a gene and in 1976, of the viral genome of bacteriophage MS2.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] Some dsDNA bacteriophages encode ribosomal proteins, which are thought to modulate protein translation during phage infection.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] In the case of the T4 phage, the construction of new virus particles involves the assistance of helper proteins that act catalytically during phage morphogenesis.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] The base plates are assembled first, with the tails being built upon them afterward.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] The head capsids, constructed separately, will spontaneously assemble with the tails.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] During assembly of the phage T4 virion, the morphogenetic proteins encoded by the phage genes interact with each other in a characteristic sequence.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] Maintaining an appropriate balance in the amounts of each of these proteins produced during viral infection appears to be critical for normal phage T4 morphogenesis.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] The DNA is packed efficiently within the heads.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] The whole process takes about 15 minutes.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] Early studies of bacteriophage T4 (1962–1964) provided an opportunity to gain understanding of virtually all of the genes that are essential for growth of the bacteriophage under laboratory conditions.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] These studies were made possible by the availability of two classes of conditional lethal mutants.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] One class of such mutants was referred to as amber mutants.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] The other class of conditional lethal mutants was referred to as temperature-sensitive mutants.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] Studies of these two classes of mutants led to considerable insight into the functions and interactions of the proteins employed in the machinery of DNA replication, repair and recombination, and on how viruses are assembled from protein and nucleic acid components (molecular morphogenesis).
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] Phages may be released via cell lysis, by extrusion, or, in a few cases, by budding.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] Lysis, by tailed phages, is achieved by an enzyme called endolysin, which attacks and breaks down the cell wall peptidoglycan.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] An altogether different phage type, the filamentous phage, makes the host cell continually secrete new virus particles.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] Released virions are described as free, and, unless defective, are capable of infecting a new bacterium.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] Budding is associated with certain *Mycoplasma* phages.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] In contrast to virion release, phages displaying a lysogenic cycle do not kill the host and instead become long-term residents as prophages.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] Research in 2017 revealed that the bacteriophage Φ3T makes a short viral protein that signals other bacteriophages to lie dormant instead of killing the host bacterium.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] Arbitrium is the name given to this protein by the researchers who discovered it.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] Given the millions of different phages in the environment, phage genomes come in a variety of forms and sizes.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] RNA phages such as MS2 have the smallest genomes, with only a few kilobases.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] However, some DNA phages such as T4 may have large genomes with hundreds of genes; the size and shape of the capsid varies along with the size of the genome.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] The largest bacteriophage genomes reach a size of 735 kb.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] Bacteriophage genomes can be highly mosaic, i.e. the genome of many phage species appear to be composed of numerous individual modules.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] These modules may be found in other phage species in different arrangements.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] Mycobacteriophages, bacteriophages with mycobacterial hosts, have provided excellent examples of this mosaicism.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] In these mycobacteriophages, genetic assortment may be the result of repeated instances of site-specific recombination and illegitimate recombination (the result of phage genome acquisition of bacterial host genetic sequences).
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] Evolutionary mechanisms shaping the genomes of bacterial viruses vary between different families and depend upon the type of the nucleic acid, characteristics of the virion structure, as well as the mode of the viral life cycle.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] Some marine roseobacter phages, also known as roseophages, contain deoxyuridine (dU) instead of deoxythymidine (dT) in their genomic DNA.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] There is some evidence that this unusual component is a mechanism to evade bacterial defense mechanisms such as restriction endonucleases and CRISPR/Cas systems which evolved to recognize and cleave sequences within invading phages, thereby inactivating them.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] Other phages have long been known to use unusual nucleotides.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] In 1963, Takahashi and Marmur identified a *Bacillus* phage that has dU substituting dT in its genome, and in 1977, Kirnos et al. identified a cyanophage containing 2-aminoadenine (Z) instead of adenine (A).
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] The field of systems biology investigates the complex networks of interactions within an organism, usually using computational tools and modeling.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] For example, a phage genome that enters into a bacterial host cell may express hundreds of phage proteins which will affect the expression of numerous host genes or the host's metabolism.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] All of these complex interactions can be described and simulated in computer models.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] For instance, infection of *Pseudomonas aeruginosa* by the temperate phage PaP3 changed the expression of 38% (2160/5633) of its host's genes.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] Many of these effects are probably indirect, hence the challenge becomes to identify the direct interactions among bacteria and phage.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] Several attempts have been made to map protein–protein interactions among phage and their host.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] For instance, bacteriophage lambda was found to interact with its host, *E. coli*, by dozens of interactions.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] Again, the significance of many of these interactions remains unclear, but these studies suggest that there most likely are several key interactions and many indirect interactions whose role remains uncharacterized.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] Bacteriophages are a major threat to bacteria and prokaryotes, which have evolved numerous mechanisms to block infection (host resistance) or to block the replication of bacteriophages within host cells (anti-phage defense).
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] Temperate phages are bacteriophages that integrate their genetic material into the host as extrachromosomal episomes or as a prophage during a lysogenic cycle.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] Bacteriophage–host symbiosis may benefit bacteria by providing selective advantages while passively replicating the phage genome.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] Metagenomics has allowed the in-water detection of bacteriophages that was not possible previously.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] Also, bacteriophages have been used in hydrological tracing and modelling in river systems, especially where surface water and groundwater interactions occur.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] The use of phages is preferred to the more conventional dye marker because they are significantly less absorbed when passing through ground waters and they are readily detected at very low concentrations.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] Non-polluted water may contain approximately 2×108 bacteriophages per ml.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] Bacteriophages are thought to contribute extensively to horizontal gene transfer in natural environments, principally via transduction, but also via transformation.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] Metagenomics-based studies also have revealed that viromes from a variety of environments harbor antibiotic-resistance genes, including those that could confer multidrug resistance.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] Recent findings have mapped the complex and intertwined arsenal of anti-phage defense tools in environmental bacteria.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] Although phages do not infect humans, there are countless phage particles in the human body, given the extensive human microbiome.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] One's phage population has been called the human phageome, including the "healthy gut phageome" (HGP) and the "diseased human phageome" (DHP).
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] The active phageome of a healthy human (i.e., actively replicating as opposed to nonreplicating, integrated prophage) has been estimated to comprise dozens to thousands of different viruses.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] There is evidence that bacteriophages and bacteria interact in the human gut microbiome both antagonistically and beneficially.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] Preliminary studies have indicated that common bacteriophages are found in 62% of healthy individuals on average, while their prevalence was reduced by 42% and 54% on average in patients with ulcerative colitis (UC) and Crohn's disease (CD).
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] Abundance of phages may also decline in the elderly.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] The most common phages in the human intestine, found worldwide, are crAssphages.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] CrAssphages are transmitted from mother to child soon after birth, and there is some evidence suggesting that they may be transmitted locally.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] Each person develops their own unique crAssphage clusters.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] CrAss-like phages also may be present in primates besides humans.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] Among the countless phages, only a few have been studied in detail, including some historically important phages that were discovered in the early days of microbial genetics.
[src:codon-reassignment/bacteriophage] These, especially the T-phage, helped to discover important principles of gene structure and function.
[src:codon-reassignment/biological-process] A **biological process** is a processes necessary for an organism to live, and therefore shapes its capacity to interact with its environment.
[src:codon-reassignment/biological-process] Biological processes are made of many chemical reactions or other events that are involved in the persistence and transformation of life forms.
[src:codon-reassignment/biological-process] Regulation of biological processes occurs when any process is modulated in its frequency, rate or extent.
[src:codon-reassignment/biological-process] Biological processes are regulated by many means; examples include the control of gene expression, protein modification or interaction with a protein or substrate molecule.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-genome-sequencing] Unlike whole genome (WG) sequencing which is typically from blood cells, such as J.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-genome-sequencing] Watson’s WG sequencing projects, saliva, epithelial cells or bone - cancer genome sequencing involves direct sequencing of primary tumor tissue, adjacent or distal normal tissue, the tumor micro environment such as fibroblast/stromal cells, or metastatic tumor sites.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-genome-sequencing] Similar to whole genome sequencing, the information generated from this technique include: identification of nucleotide bases (DNA or RNA), copy number and sequence variants, mutation status, and structural changes such as chromosomal translocations and fusion genes.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-genome-sequencing] Cancer genome sequencing is not limited to WG sequencing and can also include exome, transcriptome, micronome sequencing, and end-sequence profiling.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-genome-sequencing] These methods can be used to quantify gene expression, miRNA expression, 3D genome organization, and identify alternative splicing events in addition to sequence data.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-genome-sequencing] The first report of cancer genome sequencing appeared in 2006.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-genome-sequencing] In this study 13,023 genes were sequenced in 11 breast and 11 colorectal tumors.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-genome-sequencing] A subsequent follow up was published in 2007 where the same group added just over 5,000 more genes and almost 8,000 transcript species to complete the exomes of 11 breast and colorectal tumors.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-genome-sequencing] The first whole cancer genome to be sequenced was from cytogenetically normal acute myeloid leukaemia by Ley *et al.* in November 2008.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-genome-sequencing] The first breast cancer tumor was sequenced by Shah *et al.* in October 2009, the first lung and skin tumors by Pleasance *et al.* in January 2010, and the first prostate tumors by Berger *et al.* in February 2011.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-genome-sequencing] Historically, cancer genome sequencing efforts has been divided between transcriptome-based sequencing projects and DNA-centered efforts.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-genome-sequencing] The Cancer Genome Anatomy Project (CGAP) was first funded in 1997 with the goal of documenting the sequences of RNA transcripts in tumor cells.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-genome-sequencing] As technology improved, the CGAP expanded its goals to include the determination of gene expression profiles of cancerous, precancerous and normal tissues.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-genome-sequencing] The CGAP published the largest publicly available collection of cancer expressed sequence tags in 2003.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-genome-sequencing] The Sanger Institute's Cancer Genome Project, first funded in 2005, focuses on DNA sequencing.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-genome-sequencing] It has published a census of genes causally implicated in cancer, and a number of whole-genome resequencing screens for genes implicated in cancer.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-genome-sequencing] The International Cancer Genome Consortium (ICGC) was founded in 2007 with the goal of integrating available genomic, transcriptomic and epigenetic data from many different research groups.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-genome-sequencing] As of December 2011, the ICGC includes 45 committed projects and has data from 2,961 cancer genomes available.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-genome-sequencing] The process of tumorigenesis that transforms a normal cell to a cancerous cell involve a series of complex genetic and epigenetic changes.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-genome-sequencing] Identification and characterization of all these changes can be accomplished through various cancer genome sequencing strategies.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-genome-sequencing] The power of cancer genome sequencing lies in the heterogeneity of cancers and patients.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-genome-sequencing] Most cancers have a variety of subtypes and combined with these ‘cancer variants’ are the differences between a cancer subtype in one individual and in another individual.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-genome-sequencing] Cancer genome sequencing allows clinicians and oncologists to identify the specific and unique changes a patient has undergone to develop their cancer.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-genome-sequencing] Based on these changes, a personalized therapeutic strategy can be undertaken.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-genome-sequencing] A big contribution to cancer death and failed cancer treatment is clonal evolution at the cytogenetic level, for example as seen in acute myeloid leukaemia (AML).
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-genome-sequencing] In a Nature study published in 2011, Ding et al. identified cellular fractions characterized by common mutational changes to illustrate the heterogeneity of a particular tumor pre- and post-treatment vs. normal blood in one individual.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-genome-sequencing] These cellular factions could only have been identified through cancer genome sequencing, showing the information that sequencing can yield, and the complexity and heterogeneity of a tumor within one individual.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-genome-sequencing] Combined with these efforts, the International Cancer Genome Consortium (a larger organization) is a voluntary scientific organization that provides a forum for collaboration among the world's leading cancer and genomic researchers.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-genome-sequencing] The Cancer Genome Projects goal is to identify sequence variants and mutations critical in the development of human cancers.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-genome-sequencing] The project involves the systematic screening of coding genes and flanking splice junctions of all genes in the human genome for acquired mutations in human cancers.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-genome-sequencing] To investigate these events, the discovery sample set will include DNA from primary tumor, normal tissue (from the same individuals) and cancer cell lines.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-genome-sequencing] All results from this project are amalgamated and stored within the COSMIC cancer database.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-genome-sequencing] COSMIC also includes mutational data published in scientific literature.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-genome-sequencing] The TCGA is a multi-institutional effort to understand the molecular basis of cancer through genome analysis technologies, including large-scale genome sequencing techniques.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-genome-sequencing] Hundreds of samples are being collected, sequenced and analyzed.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-genome-sequencing] Currently the cancer tissue being collected include: central nervous system, breast, gastrointestinal, gynecologic, head and neck, hematologic, thoracic, and urologic.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-genome-sequencing] The components of the TCGA research network include: Biospecimen Core Resources, Genome Characterization Centers, Genome Sequencing Centers, Proteome Characterization Centers, a Data Coordinating Center, and Genome Data Analysis Centers.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-genome-sequencing] Each cancer type will undergo comprehensive genomic characterization and analysis.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-genome-sequencing] The data and information generated is freely available through the projects TCGA data portal.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-genome-sequencing] The ICGC’s goal is “To obtain a comprehensive description of genomic, transcriptomic and epigenomic changes in 50 different tumor types and/or subtypes which are of clinical and societal importance across the globe”.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-genome-sequencing] Cancer genome sequencing utilizes the same technology involved in whole genome sequencing.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-genome-sequencing] The history of sequencing has come a long way, originating in 1977 by two independent groups - Fredrick Sanger’s enzymatic didoxy DNA sequencing technique and the Allen Maxam and Walter Gilbert chemical degradation technique.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-genome-sequencing] Following these landmark papers, over 20 years later ‘Second Generation’ high-throughput next generation sequencing (HT-NGS) was born followed by ‘Third Generation HT-NGS technology’ in 2010.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-genome-sequencing] The figures to the right illustrate the general biological pipeline and companies involved in second and third generation HT-NGS sequencing.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-genome-sequencing] Three major second generation platforms include Roche/454 Pyro-sequencing, ABI/SOLiD sequencing by ligation, and Illumina’s bridge amplification sequencing technology.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-genome-sequencing] Three major third generation platforms include Pacific Biosciences Single Molecule Real Time (SMRT) sequencing, Oxford Nanopore sequencing, and Ion semiconductor sequencing.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-genome-sequencing] As with any genome sequencing project, the reads must be assembled to form a representation of the chromosomes being sequenced.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-genome-sequencing] With cancer genomes, this is usually done by aligning the reads to the human reference genome.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-genome-sequencing] Since even non-cancerous cells accumulate somatic mutations, it is necessary to compare sequence of the tumor to a matched normal tissue in order to discover which mutations are unique to the cancer.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-genome-sequencing] In some cancers, such as leukemia, it is not practical to match the cancer sample to a normal tissue, so a different non-cancerous tissue must be used.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-genome-sequencing] It has been estimated that discovery of all somatic mutations in a tumor would require 30-fold sequencing coverage of the tumor genome and a matched normal tissue.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-genome-sequencing] By comparison, the original draft of the human genome had approximately 65-fold coverage.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-genome-sequencing] To facilitate further improvement in somatic mutation detection in cancer, the Sequencing Quality Control Phase 2 Consortium has established a pair of tumor-normal cell lines as community reference samples and data sets for the benchmarking of cancer mutation detections.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-genome-sequencing] A major goal of cancer genome sequencing is to identify driver mutations: genetic changes which increase the mutation rate in the cell, leading to more rapid tumor evolution and metastasis.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-genome-sequencing] It is difficult to determine driver mutations from DNA sequence alone; but drivers tend to be the most commonly shared mutations amongst tumors, cluster around known oncogenes, and are tend to be non-silent.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-genome-sequencing] Passenger mutations, which are not important in the progression of the disease, are randomly distributed throughout the genome.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-genome-sequencing] It has been estimated that the average tumor carries c.a.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-genome-sequencing] 80 somatic mutations, fewer than 15 of which are expected to be drivers.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-genome-sequencing] A personal-genomics analysis requires further functional characterization of the detected mutant genes, and the development of a basic model of the origin and progression of the tumor.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-genome-sequencing] This analysis can be used to make pharmacological treatment recommendations.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-genome-sequencing] As of February 2012, this has only been done for patients clinical trials designed to assess the personal genomics approach to cancer treatment.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-genome-sequencing] A large-scale screen for somatic mutations in breast and colorectal tumors showed that many low-frequency mutations each make small contribution to cell survival.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-genome-sequencing] If cell survival is determined by many mutations of small effect, it is unlikely that genome sequencing will uncover a single "Achilles heel" target for anti-cancer drugs.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-genome-sequencing] However, somatic mutations tend to cluster in a limited number of signalling pathways, which are potential treatment targets.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-genome-sequencing] Cancers are heterogeneous populations of cells.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-genome-sequencing] When sequence data is derived from a whole tumor, information about the differences in sequence and expression pattern between cells is lost.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-genome-sequencing] This difficulty can be ameliorated by single-cell analysis.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-genome-sequencing] Clinically significant properties of tumors, including drug resistance, are sometimes caused by large-scale rearrangements of the genome, rather than single mutations.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-genome-sequencing] In this case, information about single nucleotide variants will be of limited utility.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-genome-sequencing] Cancer genome sequencing can be used to provide clinically relevant information in patients with rare or novel tumor types.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-genome-sequencing] Translating sequence information into a clinical treatment plan is highly complicated, requires experts of many different fields, and is not guaranteed to lead to an effective treatment plan.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-genome-sequencing] The *incidentalome* is the set of detected genomic variants not related to the cancer under study.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-genome-sequencing] (The term is a play on the name incidentaloma, which designates tumors and growths detected on whole-body imaging by coincidence).
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-genome-sequencing] The detection of such variants may result in additional measures such as further testing or lifestyle management.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] About 33% of deaths from cancer are caused by tobacco and alcohol, obesity, lack of fruit and vegetables in the diet and lack of exercise.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Other factors include certain infections, exposure to ionizing radiation, and environmental pollutants.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Infection with specific viruses, bacteria, and parasites causes approximately 16–18% of cancers worldwide.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] These infectious agents include *Helicobacter pylori*, hepatitis B, hepatitis C, and HPV.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Human immunodeficiency virus (HIV) does not directly cause cancer, but it causes immune deficiency that can increase the risk of cancer from other infections, sometimes up to several thousandfold.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Vaccination against the hepatitis B virus and the human papillomavirus have been shown to nearly eliminate the risk of cancers caused by these viruses.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] These environmental factors act, at least partly, by changing the genes of a cell.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Typically, many genetic changes are required before cancer develops.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Approximately 5–10% of cancers are due to inherited genetic defects.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Cancer can be detected by certain signs and symptoms or screening tests.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] It is then typically further investigated by medical imaging and confirmed by biopsy.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Early detection through screening is useful for cervical and colorectal cancer.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] The benefits of screening for breast cancer are controversial.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Cancer is often treated with some combination of radiation therapy, surgery, chemotherapy and targeted therapy.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] More personalized therapies that harness a patient's immune system are emerging in the field of cancer immunotherapy.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Palliative care is a medical specialty that delivers advanced pain and symptom management, which may be particularly important in those with advanced disease.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] The chance of survival depends on the type of cancer and extent of disease at the start of treatment.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] In children under 15 at diagnosis, the five-year survival rate in the developed world is on average 80%.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] For cancer in the United States, the average five-year survival rate is 66% for all ages.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] In 2015, about 90.5 million people worldwide had cancer.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] In 2019, annual cancer cases grew by 23.6 million people, and there were 10 million deaths worldwide, representing over the previous decade increases of 26% and 21%, respectively.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] The most common types of cancer in males are lung cancer, prostate cancer, colorectal cancer, and stomach cancer.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] In females, the most common types are breast cancer, colorectal cancer, lung cancer, and cervical cancer.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] If skin cancer other than melanoma were included in total new cancer cases each year, it would account for around 40% of cases.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] In children, acute lymphoblastic leukemia and brain tumors are most common, except in Africa, where non-Hodgkin lymphoma occurs more often.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] In 2012, about 165,000 children under 15 years of age were diagnosed with cancer.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] The risk of cancer increases significantly with age, and many cancers occur more commonly in developed countries.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Rates are increasing as more people live to an old age and as lifestyle changes occur in the developing world.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] The global total economic costs of cancer were estimated at US$1.16 trillion (equivalent to $1.71 trillion in 2025) per year as of 2010.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] The word comes from the ancient Greek καρκίνος, meaning 'crab' and 'tumor'.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Greek physicians Hippocrates and Galen, among others, noted the similarity of crabs to some tumors with swollen veins.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] The word was introduced in English in the modern medical sense around 1600.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Cancers comprise a large family of diseases that involve abnormal cell growth with the potential to invade or spread to other parts of the body.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] A neoplasm or tumor is a group of cells that have undergone unregulated growth and will often form a mass or lump, but may be distributed diffusely.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] All tumor cells show the six hallmarks of cancer.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] These characteristics are required to produce a malignant tumor.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] The progression from normal cells to cells that can form a detectable mass to cancer involves multiple steps known as malignant progression.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] When cancer begins, it produces no symptoms.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Signs and symptoms appear as the mass grows or ulcerates.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] The findings that result depend on cancer's type and location.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Many frequently occur in individuals who have other conditions.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Cancer can be difficult to diagnose and can be considered a "great imitator".
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] People may become anxious or depressed post-diagnosis.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] The risk of suicide in people with cancer is approximately double.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Local symptoms may occur due to the mass of the tumor or its ulceration.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] For example, mass effects from lung cancer can block the bronchus resulting in cough or pneumonia; esophageal cancer can cause narrowing of the esophagus, making it difficult or painful to swallow; and colorectal cancer may lead to narrowing or blockages in the bowel, affecting bowel habits.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Masses in breasts or testicles may produce observable lumps.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Ulceration can cause bleeding that can lead to symptoms such as coughing up blood (lung cancer), anemia or rectal bleeding (colon cancer), blood in the urine (bladder cancer), or abnormal vaginal bleeding (endometrial or cervical cancer).
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Although localized pain may occur in advanced cancer, the initial tumor is usually painless.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Some cancers can cause a buildup of fluid within the chest or abdomen.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Systemic symptoms may occur due to the body's response to the cancer.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] This may include fatigue, unintentional weight loss, or skin changes.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Some cancers can cause a systemic inflammatory state that leads to ongoing muscle loss and weakness, known as cachexia.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Some cancers, such as Hodgkin's disease, leukemias, and liver or kidney cancers, can cause a persistent fever.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Shortness of breath, called dyspnea, is a common symptom of cancer and its treatment.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] The causes of cancer-related dyspnea can include tumors in or around the lung, blocked airways, fluid in the lungs, pneumonia, or treatment reactions including an allergic response.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Treatment for dyspnea in patients with advanced cancer can include fans, bilevel ventilation, acupressure/reflexology and multicomponent nonpharmacological interventions.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Some systemic symptoms of cancer are caused by hormones or other molecules produced by the tumor, known as paraneoplastic syndromes.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Common paraneoplastic syndromes include hypercalcemia, which can cause altered mental state, constipation and dehydration, or hyponatremia, which can also cause altered mental status, vomiting, headaches, or seizures.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Metastasis is the spread of cancer to other locations in the body.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] The dispersed tumors are called metastatic tumors, while the original is called the primary tumor.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Most cancer deaths are due to cancer that has metastasized.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Metastasis is common in the late stages of cancer and it can occur via the blood or the lymphatic system or both.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Different types of cancers tend to metastasize to particular organs.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Overall, the most common places for metastases to occur are the lungs, liver, brain, and the bones.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] While some cancers can be cured if detected early, metastatic cancer is more difficult to treat and control.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Nevertheless, some recent treatments are demonstrating encouraging results.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] The majority of cancers, some 90–95% of cases, are due to environmental and lifestyle factors.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] The remaining 5–10% are due to inherited genetics.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] *Environmental* refers to any cause that is not inherited, such as lifestyle, economic, and behavioral factors and not merely pollution.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Common environmental factors that contribute to cancer death include tobacco use (25–30%), diet and obesity (30–35%), infections (15–20%), radiation (both ionizing and non-ionizing, up to 10%), lack of physical activity, and pollution.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Psychological stress does not appear to be a risk factor for the onset of cancer, though it may worsen outcomes in those who already have cancer.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Environmental or lifestyle factors that caused cancer to develop in an individual can be identified by analyzing mutational signatures from genomic sequencing of tumor DNA.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] For example, this can reveal if lung cancer was caused by tobacco smoke, if skin cancer was caused by UV radiation, or if secondary cancers were caused by previous chemotherapy treatment.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Cancer is generally not a transmissible disease.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Exceptions include rare transmissions that occur with pregnancies and occasional organ donors.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] However, transmissible infectious diseases such as hepatitis B, Epstein–Barr, HPV and HIV infections, can contribute to the development of cancer.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Exposure to particular substances has been linked to specific types of cancer.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] These substances are called *carcinogens*.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Tobacco smoke, for example, causes 90% of lung cancer.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Tobacco use can cause cancer throughout the body including in the mouth and throat, larynx, esophagus, stomach, bladder, kidney, cervix, colon/rectum, liver and pancreas.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Tobacco smoke contains over fifty known carcinogens, including nitrosamines and polycyclic aromatic hydrocarbons.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Tobacco is responsible for about one in five cancer deaths worldwide and about one in three in the developed world.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Lung cancer death rates in the United States have mirrored smoking patterns, with increases in smoking followed by dramatic increases in lung cancer death rates and, more recently, decreases in smoking rates since the 1950s followed by decreases in lung cancer death rates in men since 1990.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Alcohol increases the risk of cancer of the breast (in women), throat, liver, osophagus, mouth, larynx, and colon.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] In Western Europe, 10% of cancers in males and 3% of cancers in females are attributed to alcohol, especially liver and digestive tract cancers.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Cancer from work-related substance exposures may cause between 2 and 20% of cases, causing at least 200,000 deaths.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Cancers such as lung cancer and mesothelioma can come from inhaling tobacco smoke or asbestos fibers, or leukemia from exposure to benzene.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Exposure to perfluorooctanoic acid (PFOA), which is predominantly used in the production of Teflon, has been associated with an increased risk of kidney cancer.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Chemotherapy drugs such as platinum-based compounds are carcinogens that increase the risk of secondary cancers.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Azathioprine, an immunosuppressive medication, is a carcinogen that can cause primary tumors to develop.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Diet, physical inactivity, and obesity are related to up to 30–35% of cancer deaths.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] In the United States, excess body weight is associated with the development of many types of cancer and is a factor in 14–20% of cancer deaths.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] A UK study including data on over 5 million people showed higher body mass index to be related to at least 10 types of cancer and responsible for around 12,000 cases each year in that country.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Physical inactivity is believed to contribute to cancer risk, not only through its effect on body weight but also through negative effects on the immune system and endocrine system.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] More than half of the effect from the diet is due to overnutrition (eating too much), rather than from eating too few vegetables or other healthful foods.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Some specific foods are linked to specific cancers.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] A high-salt diet is linked to gastric cancer.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Aflatoxin B1, a frequent food contaminant, causes liver cancer.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Betel nut chewing can cause oral cancer.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] National differences in dietary practices may partly explain differences in cancer incidence.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] For example, gastric cancer is more common in Japan due to its high-salt diet while colon cancer is more common in the United States.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Immigrant cancer profiles mirror those of their new country, often within one generation.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Worldwide, approximately 18% of cancer deaths are related to infectious diseases.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] This proportion ranges from a high of 25% in Africa to less than 10% in the developed world.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Viruses are the usual infectious agents that cause cancer but bacteria and parasites may also play a role.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Radiation exposure such as ultraviolet radiation and radioactive material is a risk factor for cancer.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Many non-melanoma skin cancers are due to ultraviolet radiation, mostly from sunlight.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Sources of ionizing radiation include medical imaging and radon gas.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Residential exposure to radon gas has similar cancer risks as passive smoking.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Radiation is a more potent source of cancer when combined with other cancer-causing agents, such as radon plus tobacco smoke.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Radiation can cause cancer in most parts of the body, and at any age.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Children are twice as likely to develop radiation-induced leukemia as adults; radiation exposure before birth has ten times the effect.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Medical use of ionizing radiation is a small but growing source of radiation-induced cancers.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Ionizing radiation may be used to treat other cancers, but this may, in some cases, induce a second form of cancer.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] It is also used in some kinds of medical imaging.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Prolonged exposure to ultraviolet radiation from the sun can lead to melanoma and other skin malignancies.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Ultraviolet radiation, especially the non-ionizing medium wave UVB, is the cause of most non-melanoma skin cancers, which are the most common forms of cancer in the world.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Non-ionizing radio frequency radiation from mobile phones, electric power transmission and other similar sources has been described as a possible carcinogen by the World Health Organization's International Agency for Research on Cancer.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Evidence, however, has not supported a concern.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] There is no demonstrable link between mobile phone radiation and cancer risk.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Most cancers are non-hereditary (sporadic).
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Hereditary cancers are caused by inherited genetics.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Less than 0.3% of the population are carriers of a genetic mutation that has a large effect on cancer risk and these cause less than 3–10% of cancer.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] The relative risk of developing colorectal cancer (the cancer with the highest mortality) when a first-degree relative (parent, sibling or child) has been diagnosed with it is about 2.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] The corresponding relative risk is 1.5 for lung cancer, and 1.9 for prostate cancer.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] For breast cancer, the relative risk is 1.8 with a first-degree relative having developed it at 50 years of age or older, and 3.3 when the relative developed it when being younger than 50 years of age.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Taller people have an increased risk of cancer because they have more cells than shorter people.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Since height is genetically determined to a large extent, taller people have a heritable increase in cancer risk.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Some substances cause cancer primarily through their physical, rather than chemical, effects.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] A prominent example of this is prolonged exposure to asbestos, naturally occurring mineral fibers that are a major cause of mesothelioma (cancer of the serous membrane) usually the serous membrane surrounding the lungs.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Other substances in this category, including both naturally occurring and synthetic asbestos-like fibers, such as wollastonite, attapulgite, glass wool and rock wool, are believed to have similar effects.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Non-fibrous particulate materials that cause cancer include powdered metallic cobalt and nickel and crystalline silica (quartz, cristobalite and tridymite).
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Usually, physical carcinogens must get inside the body (such as through inhalation) and require years of exposure to produce cancer.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Physical trauma resulting in cancer is relatively rare.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Claims that breaking bones resulted in bone cancer, for example, have not been proven.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Similarly, physical trauma is not accepted as a cause for cervical cancer, breast cancer or brain cancer.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] One accepted source is frequent, long-term application of hot objects to the body.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] It is possible that repeated burns on the same part of the body, such as those produced by kanger and kairo heaters (charcoal hand warmers), may produce skin cancer, especially if carcinogenic chemicals are also present.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Frequent consumption of scalding hot tea may produce esophageal cancer.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Generally, it is believed that cancer arises, or a pre-existing cancer is encouraged, during the process of healing, rather than directly by the trauma.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] However, repeated injuries to the same tissues might promote excessive cell proliferation, which could then increase the odds of a cancerous mutation.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Chronic inflammation has been hypothesized to directly cause mutation.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Inflammation can contribute to proliferation, survival, angiogenesis and migration of cancer cells by influencing the tumor microenvironment.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Oncogenes build up an inflammatory pro-tumorigenic microenvironment.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Hormones also play a role in the development of cancer by promoting cell proliferation.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Insulin-like growth factors and their binding proteins play a key role in cancer cell proliferation, differentiation and apoptosis, suggesting possible involvement in carcinogenesis.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Hormones are important agents in sex-related cancers, such as cancer of the breast, endometrium, prostate, ovary and testis and also of thyroid cancer and bone cancer.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] For example, the daughters of women who have breast cancer have significantly higher levels of estrogen and progesterone than the daughters of women without breast cancer.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] These higher hormone levels may explain their higher risk of breast cancer, even in the absence of a breast-cancer gene.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Similarly, men of African ancestry have significantly higher levels of testosterone than men of European ancestry and have a correspondingly higher level of prostate cancer.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Men of Asian ancestry, with the lowest levels of testosterone-activating androstanediol glucuronide, have the lowest levels of prostate cancer.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Other factors are relevant: obese people have higher levels of some hormones associated with cancer and a higher rate of those cancers.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Women who take hormone replacement therapy have a higher risk of developing cancers associated with those hormones.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] On the other hand, people who exercise far more than average have lower levels of these hormones and lower risk of cancer.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Osteosarcoma may be promoted by growth hormones.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Some treatments and prevention approaches leverage this cause by artificially reducing hormone levels and thus discouraging hormone-sensitive cancers.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] There is an association between celiac disease and an increased risk of all cancers.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] People with untreated celiac disease have a higher risk, but this risk decreases with time after diagnosis and strict treatment.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] This may be due to the adoption of a gluten-free diet, which seems to have a protective role against the development of malignancy in people with celiac disease.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] However, the delay in diagnosis and initiation of a gluten-free diet seems to increase the risk of malignancies.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Rates of gastrointestinal cancers are increased in people with Crohn's disease and ulcerative colitis, due to chronic inflammation.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Immunomodulators and biologic agents used to treat these diseases may promote the development of extra-intestinal malignancies.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Cancer is fundamentally a disease of tissue growth regulation.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] For a normal cell to transform into a cancer cell, the genes that regulate cell growth and differentiation must be altered.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] The affected genes are divided into two broad categories.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Oncogenes are genes that promote cell growth and reproduction.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Tumor suppressor genes are genes that inhibit cell division and survival.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Malignant transformation can occur through the formation of novel oncogenes, the inappropriate over-expression of normal oncogenes, or by the under-expression or disabling of tumor suppressor genes.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Typically, changes in multiple genes are required to transform a normal cell into a cancer cell.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Genetic changes can occur at different levels and by different mechanisms.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] The gain or loss of an entire chromosome can occur through errors in mitosis.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] More common are mutations, which are changes in the nucleotide sequence of genomic DNA.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Large-scale mutations involve the deletion or gain of a portion of a chromosome.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Genomic amplification occurs when a cell gains copies (often 20 or more) of a small chromosomal locus, usually containing one or more oncogenes and adjacent genetic material.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Translocation occurs when two separate chromosomal regions become abnormally fused, often at a characteristic location.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] A well-known example of this is the Philadelphia chromosome, or translocation of chromosomes 9 and 22, which occurs in chronic myelogenous leukemia and results in production of the BCR-Abl fusion protein, an oncogenic tyrosine kinase.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Small-scale mutations include point mutations, deletions, and insertions, which may occur in the promoter region of a gene and affect its expression, or may occur in the gene's coding sequence and alter the function or stability of its protein product.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Disruption of a single gene may also result from integration of genomic material from a DNA virus or retrovirus, leading to the expression of *viral* oncogenes in the affected cell and its descendants.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Replication of the data contained within the DNA of living cells will probabilistically result in some errors (mutations).
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Complex error correction and prevention are built into the process and safeguard the cell against cancer.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] If a significant error occurs, the damaged cell can self-destruct through programmed cell death, termed apoptosis.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] If the error control processes fail, then the mutations will survive and be passed along to daughter cells.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Some environments make errors more likely to arise and propagate.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Such environments can include the presence of disruptive substances called carcinogens, repeated physical injury, heat, ionising radiation, or hypoxia.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] The transformation of a normal cell into cancer is akin to a chain reaction caused by initial errors, which compound into more severe errors, each progressively allowing the cell to escape more controls that limit normal tissue growth.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] This rebellion-like scenario is an undesirable survival of the fittest, where the driving forces of evolution work against the body's design and enforcement of order.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Once cancer has begun to develop, this ongoing process, termed *clonal evolution*, drives progression towards more invasive stages.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Clonal evolution leads to intra-tumour heterogeneity (cancer cells with heterogeneous mutations) that complicates the design of effective treatments, as therapies must account for the selective pressures they exert on the tumour cell population.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] The classical view of cancer is a set of diseases driven by progressive genetic abnormalities that include mutations in tumor-suppressor genes and oncogenes, and in chromosomal abnormalities.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] A role for epigenetic alterations was identified in the early 21st century.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Epigenetic alterations are functionally relevant modifications to the genome that do not change the nucleotide sequence.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Examples of such modifications are changes in DNA methylation (hypermethylation and hypomethylation), histone modification and changes in chromosomal architecture (caused by inappropriate expression of proteins such as HMGA2 or HMGA1).
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Each of these alterations regulates gene expression without altering the underlying DNA sequence.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] These changes may remain through cell divisions, endure for multiple generations, and can be considered as equivalent to mutations.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Epigenetic alterations occur frequently in cancers.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] As an example, one study listed protein coding genes that were frequently altered in their methylation in association with colon cancer.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] These included 147 hypermethylated and 27 hypomethylated genes.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Of the hypermethylated genes, 10 were hypermethylated in 100% of colon cancers and many others were hypermethylated in more than 50% of colon cancers.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] While epigenetic alterations are found in cancers, the epigenetic alterations in DNA repair genes, causing reduced expression of DNA repair proteins, may be of particular importance.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Such alterations may occur early in the progression to cancer and are a possible cause of the genetic instability characteristic of cancers.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Reduced expression of DNA repair genes disrupts DNA repair.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] This is shown in the figure at the 4th level from the top.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] (In the figure, red wording indicates the central role of DNA damage and defects in DNA repair in the progression to cancer.) When DNA repair is deficient DNA damage remains in cells at a higher than usual level (5th level) and causes increased frequencies of mutation and/or epimutation (6th level).
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Mutation rates increase substantially in cells defective in DNA mismatch repair or in homologous recombinational repair (HRR).
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Chromosomal rearrangements and aneuploidy (an abnormal number of chromosomes in a cell) also increase in HRR defective cells.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Higher levels of DNA damage cause increased mutation (right side of figure) and increased epimutation.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] During repair of DNA double strand breaks, or repair of other DNA damage, incompletely cleared repair sites can cause epigenetic gene silencing.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Deficient expression of DNA repair proteins due to an inherited mutation can increase cancer risks.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Individuals with an inherited impairment in any of 34 DNA repair genes (see article DNA repair-deficiency disorder) have increased cancer risk, with some defects ensuring a 100% lifetime chance of cancer (e.g. p53 mutations).
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Germline DNA repair mutations are noted on the figure's left side.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] However, such germline mutations (which cause highly penetrant cancer syndromes) are the cause of only about 1 percent of cancers.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] In sporadic cancers, deficiencies in DNA repair are occasionally caused by a mutation in a DNA repair gene but are much more frequently caused by epigenetic alterations that reduce or silence expression of DNA repair genes.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] This is indicated in the figure at the 3rd level.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Many studies of heavy metal-induced carcinogenesis show that such heavy metals cause a reduction in expression of DNA repair enzymes, some through epigenetic mechanisms.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] DNA repair inhibition is proposed to be a predominant mechanism in heavy metal-induced carcinogenicity.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] In addition, frequent epigenetic alterations of the DNA sequences code for small RNAs called microRNAs (or miRNAs). miRNAs do not code for proteins, but can "target" protein-coding genes and reduce their expression.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Cancers usually arise from an assemblage of mutations and epimutations that confer a selective advantage leading to clonal expansion (see Field defects in progression to cancer).
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Mutations, however, may not be as frequent in cancers as epigenetic alterations.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] An average cancer of the breast or colon can have about 60 to 70 protein-altering mutations, of which about three or four may be "driver" mutations and the remaining ones may be "passenger" mutations.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] The typical steps in metastasis are local invasion, intravasation (entry of cancer cells into a blood or lymph vessel), circulation through the body, extravasation (exit from the vessel into surrounding tissue), proliferation and angiogenesis (formation of new blood vessels to supply the tumour).
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Different types of cancers tend to metastasize to particular organs, but overall the most common places for metastases to occur are the lungs, liver, brain and the bones.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Normal cells typically generate about 30% of energy from glycolysis, whereas most cancers rely on glycolysis for energy production (Warburg effect).
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] But a minority of cancer types rely on oxidative phosphorylation as the primary energy source, including lymphoma, leukemia, and endometrial cancer.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Even in these cases, however, the use of glycolysis as an energy source rarely exceeds 60%.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] A few cancers use glutamine as the major energy source, partly because it provides nitrogen required for nucleotide (DNA, RNA) synthesis.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Cancer stem cells often use oxidative phosphorylation or glutamine as a primary energy source.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Most cancers are initially recognized either because of the appearance of signs or symptoms or through screening.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Neither of these leads to a definitive diagnosis, which requires the examination of a tissue sample by a pathologist.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] People with suspected cancer are investigated with medical tests.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] These commonly include blood tests, X-rays, (contrast) CT scans and endoscopy.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] The tissue diagnosis from the biopsy indicates the type of cell that is proliferating, its histological grade, genetic abnormalities and other features.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Together, this information is useful to evaluate the prognosis and to choose the best treatment.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Cytogenetics and immunohistochemistry are other types of tissue tests.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] These tests provide information about molecular changes (such as mutations, fusion genes and numerical chromosome changes) and may thus also indicate the prognosis and best treatment.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Cancer diagnosis can cause psychological distress and psychosocial interventions, such as talking therapy, may help people with this.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Some people choose to disclose the diagnosis widely; others prefer to keep the information private, especially shortly after the diagnosis, or to disclose it only partially or to selected people.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Cancers are classified by the type of cell that the tumor cells resemble and is therefore presumed to be the origin of the tumor.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Cancers are usually named using *-carcinoma*, *-sarcoma* or *-blastoma* as a suffix, with the Latin or Greek word for the organ or tissue of origin as the root.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] For example, cancers of the liver parenchyma arising from malignant epithelial cells is called *hepatocarcinoma*, while a malignancy arising from primitive liver precursor cells is called a hepatoblastoma and a cancer arising from fat cells is called a *liposarcoma*.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] For some common cancers, the English organ name is used.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] For example, the most common type of breast cancer is called *ductal carcinoma of the breast*.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Here, the adjective *ductal* refers to the appearance of cancer under the microscope, which suggests that it has originated in the milk ducts.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Benign tumors (which are not cancers) are named using *-oma* as a suffix with the organ name as the root.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] For example, a benign tumor of smooth muscle cells is called a *leiomyoma* (the common name of this frequently occurring benign tumor in the uterus is *fibroid*).
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Confusingly, some types of cancer use the *-noma* suffix, examples including melanoma and seminoma.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Some types of cancer are named for the size and shape of the cells under a microscope, such as giant cell carcinoma, spindle cell carcinoma and small-cell carcinoma.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Cancer prevention involves changes on the individual level, as well as the public policy level.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Around 40% of cancer can be prevented by avoiding or eliminating risk factors.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Cancer prevention is more cost-effective than treatment.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] On an individual level, cancer can be prevented by avoiding carcinogens such as with smoking, limiting sun exposure, maintaining a healthy weight and active lifestyle, and following medical guidance designed to decrease risk for cancer.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Public policy changes are required to expand individual access to cancer prevention interventions, as well as to address collective issues that cause cancer such as air pollution.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Due to having shared causes in common, efforts to prevent cancer often help prevent other diseases as well as improve the environment.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Cancer prevention through diet generally emphasizes broad, healthy eating habits over focusing on specific foods.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] The risk for cancer is decreased with a diet high in fiber, fruits and vegetables, and low in red and processed meat.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Replacing refined sugars with whole grains, and consuming plant-based proteins and fats also helps reduce the risk of cancer.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Maintaining a healthy body weight and being physically active helps prevent cancer.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Obesity increases the risk for cancer, partly through causing inflammation and metabolic and hormonal abnormalities.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Exercise promotes healthy immune and hormonal systems that reduce cancer.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Diets high in calcium (such as dairy products) and coffee, and low in processed meat, can help prevent colorectal cancer.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Alcohol is a group 1 carcinogen, and is responsible for around 4% of all cancer deaths.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Any amount of alcohol increases the risk for cancer.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Alcohol causes several types of cancer, through different mechanisms including the breakdown of ethanol into acetaldehyde, which damages DNA.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Alcohol increases estrogen, which contributes to the development of breast cancer.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Alcohol acts as a solvent for some carcinogens, allowing them to penetrate cells more easily.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] For instance, consuming alcohol along with tobacco helps carcinogens in tobacco penetrate the cells of the mouth and cause mouth cancer.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Smoking is the number one preventable cause of cancer.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Smoking causes at least 20 different types of cancer.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Cigars, pipes (including water pipes), and smokeless tobacco cause cancer.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] More than 1.2 million people die every year from exposure to second-hand smoke, around 100,000 of these deaths from cancer.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] The health impact of electronic cigarettes (vaping) and similar products is unknown and subject to debate.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Breastfeeding reduces the mother's risk for developing breast cancer.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Infants who breastfed are less likely to gain excess weight later in life.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] A healthy weight helps to reduce the risk for several types of cancer.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Ultraviolet radiation is the main cause of skin cancer.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] The incidence of skin cancer is increasing, and it is the most common type of cancer in lighter-skinned populations.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] UV radiation, whether from sunlight or tanning beds, directly and indirectly damages DNA.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] The most effective way to prevent skin cancer is to limit sun exposure and not use tanning beds, wear protective clothing (such as a hat), wear sunscreen, and make use of the shade.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] The best time to avoid sunlight is between 9:00 a.m. and 3:00 p.m. when UV radiation is strongest.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Even on cloudy days about 80% of UV radiation is still present.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] UV radiation does not correlate with temperature—there is just as much UV radiation from the sun on a cold day as on a hot day.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] About 10% of UVB radiation passes through glass windows.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] UV exposure during childhood is particularly harmful.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] However, the beneficial effects of sunlight exposure (such as the production of vitamin D) can be achieved while avoiding harmful amounts of sun exposure.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] The ozone layer absorbs UV radiation from the sun, reducing rates of skin cancer.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] However, atmospheric pollution has decreased the ozone layer, and increased rates of skin cancer globally.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] In 1987, an international treaty named the Montreal Protocol was signed to limit the release of ozone-damaging chemicals.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Since then the ozone layer has been recovering, and it is expected that by 2100 the Montreal Protocol will have prevented 11 million cases of melanoma in the United States.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Air pollution, both outdoor and indoor, is the largest environmental contributor to cancer.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Air pollution caused an estimated 350,167 deaths from lung cancer in 2017.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Airborne particulate matter smaller than 2.5 µm (PM2.5) is a group 1 carcinogen.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] The concentration of PM2.5 in the air is the most reliable predictor of how carcinogenic the air is.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] PM2.5 primarily comes from the burning of fuel for transportation, power generation, and industry, the burning of biomass (e.g. forest fires, stubble burning), and heating and cooking in the home.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] In 2017, an estimated 14.1% of all lung cancer deaths were caused by PM2.5 pollution.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Local PM2.5 and PM10 levels can be monitored online, and wearing a close-fitting particulate respirator reduces personal exposure when levels are high.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Exposure to cancer-causing air pollution can also be reduced by avoiding motorized transportation, selecting routes away from pollution sources such as coal plants, and keeping vehicle windows closed in heavy traffic.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Decreasing outdoor air pollution requires action on the public policy level, and involves international collaborative efforts.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Indoor air pollution includes PM2.5 from the burning of fuels, as well as other pollutants such as radon and hazardous construction materials (e.g. asbestos, glues, formaldehyde, lead).
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] In 2019, the percent of preventable cases of lung cancer by cause was estimated as 62% for smoking, 15% for PM2.5 in outdoor air, 5.8% for secondhand smoke, 4% from using solid fuels for cooking, and 4% for radon.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Individuals can decrease air pollution in the home by using clean fuels, maintaining adequate ventilation, and using air purifiers.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Around 80% of ionizing radiation that people are exposed to comes from natural sources, around half of which comes from breathing in radioactive radon gas.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Radon is produced by the decay of uranium in the ground, becoming a radioactive gas that can accumulate in the buildings above it.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Exposure to radon can be reduced by testing homes and, when found to be high, taking steps to reduce indoor radon levels.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] The primary method to reduce indoor radon levels is a vent pipe system and fan, which pulls radon from beneath the building and vents it to the outside.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Around 20% of ionizing radiation that people are exposed to comes from artificial sources, primarily from x-rays used for medical imaging.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] CT scans, which take x-rays at many angles to produce a 3D image, expose patients to a higher level of radiation than standard 2D x-rays.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Cancer prevention focuses on avoiding unnecessary diagnostic procedures, and minimizing the dose of ionizing radiation that patients are exposed to during these procedures.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] There have been 38 workplace chemicals and 12 workplace circumstances classified as carcinogenic, and 41 chemicals and 6 circumstances classified as probably carcinogenic.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Despite being known to cause cancer, workers are still commonly exposed to silica, diesel engine exhaust, heavy metals, asbestos, and polycyclic aromatic hydrocarbons.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Occupational cancer can be reduced, and in recent decades successful regulations and programs have reduced or eliminated exposure to certain carcinogens in the workplace.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Prevention involves decreasing the use of certain chemicals and if this isn't possible limiting exposure to these substances, a process known as hierarchy of controls.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Occupational cancer can also be prevented by improving workplace procedures and training, and by using personal protective equipment.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] In 2018, 2.2 million cases of cancer were caused by infection, primarily by *Helicobacter pylori* (810,000), human papillomavirus (690,000), hepatitis B (360,000), and hepatitis C (160,000).
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] All four of these infections can either be vaccinated against or treated, and collectively they cause more than 90% of infection-related cancers worldwide.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Medications can be used to prevent cancer in a few circumstances.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] In the general population, NSAIDs reduce the risk of colorectal cancer; however, due to cardiovascular and gastrointestinal side effects, they cause more harm than benefit when used for prevention.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Aspirin is not recommended for reducing cancer risk.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] COX-2 inhibitors may decrease the rate of polyp formation in people with familial adenomatous polyposis; however, it is associated with the same adverse effects as NSAIDs.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Women who have an increased risk for breast cancer can lower their chances of getting breast cancer by taking tamoxifen, raloxifene, or aromatase inhibitors.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] No vitamin, multivitamin, or nutritional supplement is recommended for the prevention of cancer.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Vitamin E supplements do not prevent cancer, and beta-carotene supplements increase the odds of lung cancer in those already at a high risk for it.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Hormone-sensitive cancers are dependent on hormones for growth and survival.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Medications that effect hormone levels may therefore have a harmful or beneficial effect on cancer rates.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Women who are on, or recently took, combined oral contraceptives (COCs) have an increased risk for breast cancer and cervical cancer.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] However, CBCs also decrease the risk for ovarian cancer, and this protective effect continues years after stopping their use.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Estrogen-only menopausal hormone therapy increases the risk of breast, endometrial, and ovarian cancer.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p01] Combined estrogen–progestogen hormone therapy increases the risk of breast and endometrial cancer.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p02] Unlike diagnostic efforts prompted by symptoms and medical signs, cancer screening involves efforts to detect cancer after it has formed, but before any noticeable symptoms appear.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p02] This may involve physical examination, blood or urine tests or medical imaging.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p02] Cancer screening is not available for many types of cancers.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p02] Even when tests are available, they may not be recommended for everyone.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p02] *Universal screening* or *mass screening* involves screening everyone.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p02] *Selective screening* identifies people who are at higher risk, such as people with a family history.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p02] Several factors are considered to determine whether the benefits of screening outweigh the risks and the costs of screening.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p02] Screens for gastric cancer using photofluorography due to the high incidence there.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p02] Genetic testing for individuals at high risk of certain cancers is recommended by unofficial groups.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p02] Carriers of these mutations may then undergo enhanced surveillance, chemoprevention, or preventative surgery to reduce their subsequent risk.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p02] Many treatment options for cancer exist.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p02] The primary ones include surgery, chemotherapy, radiation therapy, hormonal therapy, targeted therapy and palliative care.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p02] Which treatments are used depends on the type, location and grade of the cancer as well as the patient's health and preferences.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p02] The treatment intent may or may not be curative.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p02] Chemotherapy is the treatment of cancer with one or more cytotoxic anti-neoplastic drugs (chemotherapeutic agents) as part of a standardized regimen.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p02] The term encompasses a variety of drugs, which are divided into broad categories such as alkylating agents and antimetabolites.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p02] Traditional chemotherapeutic agents act by killing cells that divide rapidly, a critical property of most cancer cells.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p02] It was found that providing combined cytotoxic drugs is better than a single drug, a process called the combination therapy, which has an advantage in the statistics of survival and response to the tumor and in the progress of the disease.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p02] A Cochrane review concluded that combined therapy was more effective in treating metastasized breast cancer.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p02] However, generally it is not certain whether combination chemotherapy leads to better health outcomes, when both survival and toxicity are considered.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p02] Targeted therapy is a form of chemotherapy that targets specific molecular differences between cancer and normal cells.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p02] The first targeted therapies blocked the estrogen receptor molecule, inhibiting the growth of breast cancer.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p02] Another common example is the class of Bcr-Abl inhibitors, which are used to treat chronic myelogenous leukemia (CML).
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p02] Currently, targeted therapies exist for many of the most common cancer types, including bladder cancer, breast cancer, colorectal cancer, kidney cancer, leukemia, liver cancer, lung cancer, lymphoma, pancreatic cancer, prostate cancer, skin cancer, and thyroid cancer as well as other cancer types.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p02] The efficacy of chemotherapy depends on the type of cancer and the stage.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p02] In combination with surgery, chemotherapy has proven useful in cancer types including breast cancer, colorectal cancer, pancreatic cancer, osteogenic sarcoma, testicular cancer, ovarian cancer and certain lung cancers.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p02] Chemotherapy is curative for some cancers, such as some leukemias, ineffective in some brain tumors, and needless in others, such as most non-melanoma skin cancers.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p02] The effectiveness of chemotherapy is often limited by its toxicity to other tissues in the body.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p02] Even when chemotherapy does not provide a permanent cure, it may be useful to reduce symptoms such as pain or to reduce the size of an inoperable tumor in the hope that surgery will become possible in the future.*Wang M, Zhang C, Yang G, Shi Y (March 2017).
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p02] "Neoadjuvant Chemotherapy Creates Surgery Opportunities For Inoperable Locally Advanced Breast Cancer".
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p02] Radiation therapy involves the use of ionizing radiation in an attempt to either cure or improve symptoms.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p02] It works by damaging the DNA of cancerous tissue, causing mitotic catastrophe resulting in the death of the cancer cells.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p02] To spare normal tissues (such as skin or organs, which radiation must pass through to treat the tumor), shaped radiation beams are aimed from multiple exposure angles to intersect at the tumor, providing a much larger dose there than in the surrounding, healthy tissue.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p02] As with chemotherapy, cancers vary in their response to radiation therapy.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p02] Radiation therapy is used in about half of cases.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p02] The radiation can be either from internal sources (brachytherapy) or external sources.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p02] The radiation is most commonly low energy X-rays for treating skin cancers, while higher energy X-rays are used for cancers within the body.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p02] Radiation is typically used in addition to surgery and/or chemotherapy.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p02] For certain types of cancer, such as early head and neck cancer, it may be used alone.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p02] Radiation therapy after surgery for brain metastases has been shown to not improve overall survival in patients compared to surgery alone.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p02] For painful bone metastasis, radiation therapy has been found to be effective in about 70% of patients.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p02] Surgery is the primary method of treatment for most isolated, solid cancers and may play a role in palliation and prolongation of survival.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p02] It is typically an important part of the definitive diagnosis and staging of tumors, as biopsies are usually required.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p02] In localized cancer, surgery typically attempts to remove the entire mass along with, in certain cases, the lymph nodes in the area.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p02] For some types of cancer this is sufficient to eliminate the cancer.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p02] Palliative care may be confused with hospice and therefore only indicated when people approach end of life.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p02] Like hospice care, palliative care attempts to help the patient cope with their immediate needs and to increase comfort.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p02] Unlike hospice care, palliative care does not require people to stop treatment aimed at the cancer.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p02] Multiple national medical guidelines recommend early palliative care for patients whose cancer has produced distressing symptoms or who need help coping with their illness.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p02] In patients first diagnosed with metastatic disease, palliative care may be immediately indicated.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p02] Palliative care is indicated for patients with a prognosis of less than 12 months of life even given aggressive treatment.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p02] A variety of therapies using immunotherapy, stimulating or helping the immune system to fight cancer, have come into use since 1997.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p02] Laser therapy uses high-intensity light to treat cancer by shrinking or destroying tumors or precancerous growths.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p02] Lasers are most commonly used to treat superficial cancers that are on the surface of the body or the lining of internal organs.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p02] It is used to treat basal cell skin cancer and the very early stages of others like cervical, penile, vaginal, vulvar, and non-small cell lung cancer.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p02] It is often combined with other treatments, such as surgery, chemotherapy, or radiation therapy.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p02] Laser-induced interstitial thermotherapy (LITT), or interstitial laser photocoagulation, uses lasers to treat some cancers using hyperthermia, which uses heat to shrink tumors by damaging or killing cancer cells.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p02] Lasers are more precise than surgery and cause less damage, pain, bleeding, swelling, and scarring.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p02] A disadvantage is that surgeons must have specialized training.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p02] It may be more expensive than other treatments.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p02] Complementary and alternative cancer treatments are a diverse group of therapies, practices and products that are not part of conventional medicine.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p02] "Complementary medicine" refers to methods and substances used along with conventional medicine, while "alternative medicine" refers to compounds used instead of conventional medicine.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p02] Most complementary and alternative medicines for cancer have not been studied or tested using conventional techniques such as clinical trials.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p02] Some alternative treatments have been investigated and shown to be ineffective but still continue to be marketed and promoted.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p02] Survival rates vary by cancer type and by the stage at which it is diagnosed, ranging from majority survival to complete mortality five years after diagnosis.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p02] Once a cancer has metastasized, prognosis normally becomes much worse.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p02] About half of patients receiving treatment for invasive cancer (excluding carcinoma *in situ* and non-melanoma skin cancers) die from that cancer or its treatment.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p02] A majority of cancer deaths are due to metastases of the primary tumor.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p02] Survival is worse in the developing world, partly because the types of cancer that are most common there are harder to treat than those associated with developed countries.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p02] Those who survive cancer develop a second primary cancer at about twice the rate of those never diagnosed.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p02] Predicting short- or long-term survival depends on many factors.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p02] The most important are the cancer type and the patient's age and overall health.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p02] Those who are frail with other health problems have lower survival rates than otherwise healthy people.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p02] Centenarians are unlikely to survive for five years even if treatment is successful.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p02] People who report a higher quality of life tend to survive longer.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p02] People with lower quality of life may be affected by depression and other complications and/or disease progression that both impairs quality and quantity of life.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p02] Additionally, patients with worse prognoses may be depressed or report poorer quality of life because they perceive that their condition is likely to be fatal.*Satin JR, Linden W, Phillips MJ (November 2009).
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p02] "Depression as a predictor of disease progression and mortality in cancer patients: a meta-analysis".
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p02] People with cancer have an increased risk of blood clots in their veins which can be life-threatening.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p02] The use of blood thinners such as heparin decrease the risk of blood clots but have not been shown to increase survival in people with cancer.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p02] People who take blood thinners also have an increased risk of bleeding.
[src:codon-reassignment/cancer-p02] Although extremely rare, some forms of cancer, even from an advanced stage, can heal spontaneously.
